<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hershiser Works Out Glitches  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) -- Orel Hershiser, intent on making a
contribution to the Los Angeles Dodgers in the second half of the
season, made his first appearance in a minor league game in nine
years Tuesday night for Class-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser pitched six innings against Lancaster, allowing one
unearned run and four hits. He threw 71 pitches -- 49 for strikes --
while allowing a walk and striking out two.
</P>
<P>
   He left the game trailing 1-0, but the Stampede tied it in the
bottom of the sixth with a home run. Hershiser's next scheduled
start for San Bernardino will be on June 5 at Rancho Cucamonga.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, who was demoted to the bullpen last month and hasn't
pitched for the Dodgers since May 9, asked general manager Kevin
Malone on more than one occasion to option him to the minors. His
desire was to get in some competitive work and correct the flaws
that led to a 10.70 ERA and a 1-2 record in seven appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Under baseball's collective bargaining agreement, the 18-year
major league veteran could have refused to be sent to the minors.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, 41, has not pitched in a game since May 9, and
struggled with control problems -- tying a modern major league
record by hitting four batters in just 1 1-3 innings on April 19
against Houston at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser was the 1988 Cy Young winner and World Series MVP
after pitching a major league record 59 consecutive scoreless
innings that season. He has a career record of 204-147, including a
career-high 23 wins in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's outing marked Hershiser's first appearance in the
minors since 1991, when he made four starts for three Dodgers' farm
teams in his rehabilitation from reconstructive shoulder surgery.
Other than that, he hasn't pitched in the minors in 17 years, since
he first came up to the Dodgers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
