<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio campaign maps strategy for beating Hillary Clinton  </HEADLINE>
By FRANK ELTMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- New York Republicans say if Rick Lazio
wants a shot at being the state's next United States senator, he's
going to have to be a regular visitor to upstate New York
</P>
<P>
   ''I think upstate wants to support him, they want to know more
about him,'' said Jim Mumpton of Rome. ''I think the anti-Hillary
vote is out there ... and now with just a little more oomph, I
think he can do it.''
</P>
<P>
   In accepting his party's nomination to run against Democrat
Hillary Rodham Clinton on Tuesday, Lazio emphasized his home-town
boy image while painting his opponent as an outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have one advantage she will never have: I can be myself,''
Lazio told Republicans at the state Republican Party nominating
convention. ''I am a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   The little-known four-term congressman from Long Island also
sought to deflect criticism from the Clinton camp, which has
portrayed him as a radical right-winger.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some in the opposition camp think they have a winning strategy
to repeat Newt Gingrich's name a thousand times between now and
November,'' he said. ''Well, let me share with you my winning
strategy: Let the other side pursue the politics of discord and
division.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Kosty, the Schuyler County chairwoman and Watkins Glen
village clerk and treasurer, said she was enthusiastic about Lazio,
but that he needs to get himself known.
</P>
<P>
   ''His past record certainly speaks for itself,'' said Kosty. ''I
think he needs a little more name recognition. He has to come out
and visit everyone upstate, so they get to know him. Most people in
our area will be very impressed with his family values.''
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Donald, chimed in: ''And he's from New York
state.''
</P>
<P>
   Jean Kosty said she is actually happier with Lazio than
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that Mayor Giuliani did a lot for the city, there's no
question about that,'' she said. ''But I think there is more than
the city to New York and I think Lazio will get the downstate
people, where he's from, and will have a better chance of getting
the upstate vote because he's gonna take the time and come and
visit us. I don't know if Rudy would have done that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
