<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb loses out as CIBA Vision buys Wesley Jessen for $785 million </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. abandoned its pursuit
of Wesley Jessen VisionCare Inc. after the Des Plaines, Ill.-based
cosmetic contact lens maker revealed it had accepted a $785 million
buyout offer from CIBA Vision.
</P>
<P>
   The deal announced Tuesday with Atlanta-based CIBA, the eye-care
unit of Swiss pharmaceutical giant Novartis, tops a sweetened but
hostile bid valued at about $725 million that Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc.
made for Wesley Jessen on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   Novartis said the combined CIBA-Wesley Jessen would be the
world's second largest contact lens company, with combined annual
sales of $1.4 billion and a work force of 8,900.
</P>
<P>
   In approving CIBA's cash offer of $38.50 a share in cash, Wesley
Jessen's board broke off its proposed merger with Ocular Sciences
Inc. and paid the contact lens company in South San Francisco a $25
million termination fee.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb's ''best and final'' bid of $35.55 a share in cash
had been set to expire today. But the eye-care company, which has
strength in premium disposable lenses, cited the definitive
agreement between Wesley Jessen and CIBA in withdrawing its offer.
</P>
<P>
   Chief executive William Carpenter said ''we considered the
acquisition of Wesley Jessen to be strategically appropriate ...
but only at a price that is attractive to the Bausch &AMP; Lomb
shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen controls about two-thirds of the highly profitable
cosmetic color-lens market. It had $311.7 million in sales last
year.
</P>
<P>
   The CIBA offer represents a 55 percent premium over Wesley
Jessen's closing price March 22, the last trading day before Bausch
&AMP; Lomb announced its original, $34-a-share bid.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is expected to be completed in the third quarter and is
subject to 51 percent of the Wesley Jessen shares being tendered to
Novartis as well as other regulatory and customary conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen has postponed indefinitely its annual shareholder
meeting, which was scheduled for June 23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
