<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio fills day to get name, message out  </HEADLINE>
By CAROLYN THOMPSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Rick Lazio talked economics with supporters
over breakfast, laid out his platform for Republican women at lunch
and blew kisses at a baseball park in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio is determined to raise his recognition level while
accepting his party's U.S. Senate nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Standing amid supporters at a meet-the-candidate lunch Tuesday
he declared ''we have 150 days ... to prove who we are.''
</P>
<P>
   The candidate who promised to go ''block by block, house by
house'' to earn the support of New Yorkers could have started with
the little dry cleaning store next door to the luncheon site.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't heard of him,'' said Suzanna Mancuso, who was
vacuuming the store while the Long Island congressman geared up to
accept his party's nomination later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio had the support of passer-by Chris Weinert -- not for who
he is, but for who he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll vote against Hillary Rodham Clinton,'' Weinert said.
</P>
<P>
   It was a start.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio filled his day with a handful of campaign stops in hopes
of wooing crucial upstate voters, the majority of whom had not
heard his name until he stepped into the race 11 days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He started by talking policy over cherry danish with Erie County
Executive Joel Giambra and about a dozen Buffalo-area residents at
a Greek restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   He finished with by boarding his shiny new ''Mainstream
Express'' bus -- unveiled in a sea of red, white and blue confetti,
streamers and fireworks -- and setting out on a three-day tour of
the state.
</P>
<P>
   To several potential voters yet unfamiliar with Lazio's
politics, his strongest attribute appeared to be his status as a
New York native, a point he stressed often.
</P>
<P>
   ''The main thing is the fact that he's a New Yorker. He wants to
keep a New Yorker in office. So do I,'' said Sam Filippone, who was
among those who had breakfast with Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton was probably all right when she was in
Arkansas,'' Filippone said.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a good place for her,'' chimed his brother, Robert.
</P>
<P>
   ''But this is New York,'' Sam Filippone finished.
</P>
<P>
   After breakfast, it was on to lunch with the ''Women for
Lazio,'' where he shook hands and traded small talk at the
$25-a-plate luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Nickola hadn't heard much about Lazio before he replaced
Giuliani, but she liked what she saw so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's come out swinging,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-31-00 0013 </TRAILER>
