<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio hits the trail in the ''Mainstream Express''  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Riding his ''Mainstream Express'' campaign
bus, newly nominated Republican Senate candidate Rick Lazio has set
off across New York in search of votes for his battle against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Pledging to take ''our message of hope, opportunity and
responsibility'' on the road, the Long Island congressman was the
unanimous pick Tuesday of his party's state convention to take on
the first lady.
</P>
<P>
   With the ''Rocky'' theme blaring from loudspeakers and sporting
a fat lip courtesy of a tumble during a Memorial Day parade on
Monday, Lazio took the convention stage at a Buffalo hotel to
declare: ''I am the underdog in this race.''
</P>
<P>
   ''My opponent is better financed and better known. She comes to
New York with the support of every left-wing special interest, from
Washington insiders to the Hollywood elite,'' Lazio told more than
400 cheering delegates and over 1,000 more in attendance in a more
than 25-minute speech.
</P>
<P>
   And, pressing a favorite Republican theme -- that Clinton is a
carpetbagger -- Lazio said, ''I have one advantage she'll never have
-- I can be myself. I am a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   While not criticizing Clinton by name, Lazio accused ''the
opposition camp'' of practicing the ''politics of division ... It
is a bleak, angry place, built of fear. And I will not go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the congressman
had ''offered the people of New York recycled insults and rhetoric
that doesn't match his record. Time and time again Rick Lazio has
voted against New York's working families in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton has been running an inclusive campaign since
day one and fighting for children and families for thirty years,''
Wolfson added. ''New Yorkers will always be able to count on
Hillary to stand up for them in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Emulating Bill Clinton's successful 1992 presidential campaign
and Sen. John McCain's failed run for the White House this year,
Lazio left the convention for a three-day bus trip across the state
on his customized cruiser dubbed ''The Mainstream Express'' by
campaign aides who used to work on the McCain campaign. The
senator's bus was called ''The Straight Talk Express.''
</P>
<P>
   After a stop at a Buffalo baseball park for a rally Tuesday
evening, Lazio headed for Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the congressman planned to visit a Syracuse-area milk
plant before heading to the Finger Lakes for a stop at a winery and
a walk through the village of Wartkins Glen. Also scheduled was a
visit to the Corning Glass Museum and rallies in Elmira and
Binghamton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, meanwhile, planned a rally with supporters today in New
York City and a visit to a school in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   For Lazio, 42, the GOP nomination marked the culmination of a
dream that seemed dashed just nine months ago when Gov. George
Pataki convinced the congressman to suspend his fledgling Senate
campaign in favor of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's expected run.
</P>
<P>
   The dream was reborn on May 19 when the New York City mayor
announced he was leaving the Senate race because of prostate
cancer. Pataki and other Republican leaders quickly rallied around
the little-known Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Since entering the race, Lazio has been stressing his New York
roots, a none-too-subtle reminder that Clinton only moved into the
state in January. And, he has pointed to his record as a four-term
congressman who helped overhaul the nation's public housing system,
worked to protect the environment and voted to raise the minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton camp, on the other hand, portrays Lazio as a
conservative out of step with mainstream New Yorkers. Clinton aides
have repeatedly pointed to Lazio's support for eight out of 10
proposals from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's ''Contract with
America.'' She has also taken her rival to task for saying he's a
supporter of abortion rights, noting he has regularly voted to cut
federal Medicaid funding for poor women's abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton and Giuliani, Lazio has also come out in favor of
banning the late-term abortion procedure that critics called
''partial-birth abortion.'' That has cleared the way for him to
pick up the endorsement of the state's Conservative Party. No
Republican has won statewide office in New York since 1974 without
Conservative Party backing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
