<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 00:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boeing, Sikorsky Get Copter Contract  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOLSOM, Pa. (AP) -- The Army's next generation of armed
reconnaissance helicopter will be made by Boeing Co.'s helicopter
division in this Philadelphia suburb and at United Technologies
Corp.'s Sikorsky aircraft unit in Stratford, Conn., a Boeing
official said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract to make 13 RAH-66 Comanche helicopters is worth
$3.1 billion, Boeing spokeswoman Madelyn Bush said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a big deal for us because it helps us maintain our
employment base and gives us opportunity for future growth,'' Bush
told The Philadelphia Inquirer for Wednesday's editions.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing employs about 500 people at its helicopter plant to work
on the Comanche, and about 70 more people should be hired for it
over the next year, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing employees could be transferred from other areas of the
5,300-employee helicopter operations to the new Comanche jobs, Bush
said. If the new helicopter reaches full production by 2008, as
planned, about 1,200 Boeing workers are expected to be assigned to
the Comanche, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract is part of a helicopter modernization plan the Army
unveiled last month that affirmed a commitment to buy 1,213
new-generation Comanche reconnaissance helicopters for $38 billion
over the next 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopters will be assembled in at Boeing's helicopter
operations here and at Sikorsky's operations in Stratford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing and Sikorsky have been working together on the two-seat
helicopter for more than 10 years. It is designed to circumvent
radar and manage the flow of data among military personnel,
vehicles on the ground and aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   Company and Army officials plan to sign the contract in
Huntsville, Ala., on Thursday, Bush said. The Army manages the
contract from Huntsville.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
