<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Expands Clean-Air Study
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court drew gasps from environmentalists and
praise from industry representatives Tuesday by expanding its review of a major
clean-air dispute. The justices said they will decide whether anti-pollution
regulations must take the costs of compliance -- not just health effects -- into
account. At stake is air quality nationwide. ''It's been a bedrock principle of
the Clean Air Act that the amount of pollution allowed in the air should depend
on how it affects the health of our children and the elderly,'' said Vickie
Patton, a lawyer with the group Environmental Defense. She said a change in the
clean air policy would ''tip the scales'' away from health and toward economic
concerns.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
E-mail Rips Gore on Environment
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A Sierra Club board member wrote colleagues six months ago
to urge they not endorse Al Gore, arguing the vice president had a ''tawdry
environmental record'' and left natural resources ''hostage to the highest
bidder,'' an internal e-mail shows. ''With this legacy, no real environmentalist
could ever endorse Al Gore,'' Michael Dorsey wrote in a message released by the
Republican National Committee.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ethiopia, Eritrea Open Talks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) -- Ethiopia opened talks with Eritrea on Tuesday,
saying it had already won most of its aims through war and boasting that its
18-day offensive had forced its humbled neighbor to seek peace. Ethiopia
announced hours before the talks started in Algiers that it was withdrawing from
one front seized in the latest flare-up of the Horn of Africa countries'
2-year-old border war. But a rumble of artillery in the jagged mountains of
southern Eritrea indicated the conflict may not yet be over.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Former Pa. Gov. Casey Dies at 68
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Former Gov. Robert P. Casey, the strong-willed
Scranton Irishman who spoke passionately against abortion and overcame 20 years
of dashed hopes to become governor, died Tuesday. He was 68. Casey suffered from
a genetic condition called familial amyloidosis, which forced him to undergo a
rare heart-liver transplant in 1993. In 1997, Casey was diagnosed with prostate
cancer and underwent radiation treatments.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Northwest Attendants Ratify Contract
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Northwest Airlines flight attendants on Tuesday ratified
a five-year contract that raises their pay between 29 percent and 120 percent.
According to unofficial returns, 68 percent voted to approve the contract while
32 percent voted against it. The contract goes into effect June 1. The wage
increase would place Northwest second only to nonunion Delta Air Lines among
major carriers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Alaska Air Plans To Fire Two Pilots
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Alaska Airlines said Tuesday it will fire two pilots for
continuing a flight after they failed to properly pressurize the cabin. The
action by the pilots left about half the passengers without an emergency oxygen
source and could have caused death or brain damage if the aircraft had lost
pressure during the high-altitude portion of the March 25 flight, a Federal
Aviation Administration inspector has said. The airline notified the pilots,
Capt. Michael Alan Reese, 56, and First Officer Vincent Emile Danet, 38, of its
intent to fire them, Alaska Airlines spokesman Jack Evans said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Jump
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks rose Wednesday morning on buying of technology
issues following big gains on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average jumped
298.75 points to 16,527.65 at the end of the morning session. In New York on
Tuesday, the Nasdaq composite index ended up 254.37 points, or 7.9 percent, to
3,459.48 points -- the largest percentage gain ever for the index and the
second-largest point gain ever. Also on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial
average gained 227.89 points to close at 10,527.13 on Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Trail Blazers Defeat Lakers 96-88
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Scottie Pippen and the rest of the Portland Trail Blazers
stunned the Los Angeles Lakers with a 96-88 victory Tuesday night to stay alive
in the Western Conference finals. With Los Angeles up 3-2, the series shifts
back to Portland for Game 6 on Friday night. The Lakers lost two in a row at
home for the first time all season.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils Defeat Stars 7-3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Petr Sykora scored twice in a four-point night
and Ken Daneyko, who has played every postseason game in Devils history, scored
his first playoff goal in five seasons as New Jersey defeated the Dallas Stars
7-3 Tuesday night. Sykora also assisted on Jason Arnott's two goals as the
Devils, attempting to become the first Eastern Conference team to win the
Stanley Cup since they did it five years ago, badly outplayed the defending
champions at their own game.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
