<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rockies 10, Astros 7  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Todd Helton finally didn't have a multihit game.
And he still drove in the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   After the Rockies wasted a four-run lead, Helton put Colorado
ahead for good with a bases-loaded walk in the eighth inning as the
Rockies beat the Houston Astros 10-7 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Helton, who leads the major leagues with a .420 average, went
1-for-1 with three walks, giving him 12 hits in his last 17 at-bats
(.706). He is hitting .500 at home (44-for-88).
</P>
<P>
   Colorado, which led 4-0 and 6-3, fell behind 7-6 in the eighth
when Mitch Meluskey's two-run single off Stan Belinda (1-0).
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin tied it with an RBI single off Marc Valdes (1-1) in
the bottom half and Yorkis Perez walked Helton on a 3-2 pitch with
the bases loaded. Darren Bragg added a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Berkman homered and drove in a career-high four runs for
Houston, which has lost eight straight road games. Richard Hidalgo
went 2-for-3 with three runs scored and is 15-for-31 (.484) in his
last eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Goodwin had three hits and two RBIs for the Rockies (27-22),
who moved five games over .500 for the first time since Sept. 25,
1997 (82-77) Jose Jiminez pitched the ninth for his ninth save.
</P>
<P>
   Houston starter Scott Elarton allowed six runs and nine hits in
six innings, while Colorado's Kevin Jarvis gave up five runs and 10
hits in five-plus innings.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado took a 2-0 lead in the first on Mike Lansing's RBI
double and Helton's sacrifice fly, and Goodwin added another RBI in
the second. Jeffrey Hammonds made it 4-0 with a run-scoring single
in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Lance Berkman hit an opposite-field, three-run homer in the
fourth, but the Rockies made it 6-3 in the fifth on Darren Bragg's
RBI single and Brent Mayne's sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Houston closed to 6-5 in the fifth on RBI grounders by Lance
Berkman and Daryle Ward.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Toby Harrah managed the Rockies while manager Buddy Bell
was in Cincinnati attending his daughter's graduation. ... Houston
homered for the 17th straight game, extending its team record. ...
Ken Caminiti left in the sixth inning with a mild sprained right
hamstring.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0121 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
