<HEADLINE> Cardinals 6, Diamondbacks 1  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Shawon Dunston hit a grand slam in the sixth,
then was ejected two innings later as the St. Louis Cardinals beat
the Arizona Diamondbacks 6-1 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Ankiel (5-2) didn't allow a hit until Arizona pitcher Omar
Daal (2-6) reached on a bunt single with no outs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Matheny put the Cardinals ahead with a sacrifice fly in the
fifth, and Dunston homered in the sixth following a two-out double
by Jim Edmonds, an intentional walk to Mark McGwire and an infield
hit by Eric Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston followed with a 372-foot drive to left, his fourth homer
of the season and the fourth slam of his career.
</P>
<P>
   Dunston tripled over the head of center fielder Steve Finley in
the eighth, but was thrown out at home by shortstop Tony Womack
when he tried to stretch it to an inside-the-park homer. Dunston
argued with first-base ump Greg Gibson, who slid down the line to
make the call.
</P>
<P>
   Replays appeared to show that Dunston's foot was on home before
Kelly Stinnett applied the tag.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar Renteria had a RBI single in the ninth for St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Ankiel allowed one run -- Womack's sixth-inning sacrifice fly --
and three hits in six innings. Matt Morris allowed two hits in
three scoreless innings for his first career save.
</P>
<P>
   Daal gave up five runs and seven hits in 6 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Womack went 0-for-3, ending his hitting streak at 24 games, the
longest in the major leagues this season.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire went 0-for-2. He has not homered in 26 plate
appearances, going 4-for-17 with nine walks and five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Although the Diamondbacks are the winningest expansion team
ever, the Cardinals are 13-6 against them. ... The Cardinals had
gone homerless for two games -- the first time that happened all
season -- before Dunston's blast. ... LHP Jesse Orosco, coming off
an injured left elbow, joined Peoria of the Class A Midwest League
on Tuesday and threw 15 pitches at the start of his rehabilitation
assignment. Cardinals manager Tony La Russa said Orosco would throw
again Wednesday and then be re-evaluated. ... The Diamondbacks set
a franchise record by going 22 innings with scoring a run -- from
the third inning of a game Sunday against Milwaukee until the sixth
of this one.
</P>
