<HEADLINE> Spanish Govt Buys Goya Letters  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- The Spanish government has paid $700,000
for 40 letters the 18th-century Spanish master Francisco de Goya
wrote to a childhood friend, discussing everything from life as
royal court painter to the money he sent home to his mother.
</P>
<P>
   The government exercised its right of first refusal and snapped
up the letters Tuesday just as a private collector bidding by
telephone was about to acquire them from a historian who had put
them up for auction, the news agency Efe said.
</P>
<P>
   The letters are part of a faithful correspondence Goya carried
on with lifelong friend Martin Zapater, who lived in their hometown
of Zaragoza in northeast Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Zapater was a merchant who served as de facto administrator of
the money Goya sent home to support his mother in Zaragoza while
serving as royal court artist to kings Carlos III and Carlos IV in
Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   The missives will join 58 others between the two men that are
part of the Prado Museum's collection.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0132 </TRAILER>
