<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Puerto Rican Senator Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) -- Former Puerto Rican Sen. Edgardo
Rosario Burgos has been sentenced to three years of probation for
his role in a scheme to steal millions of dollars in federal funds
meant for AIDS patients.
</P>
<P>
   The former senator from northern Arecibo also was ordered on
Tuesday to pay a $50,000 fine and perform 500 hours of community
service.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario Burgos, a doctor, pleaded guilty in February 1999 to a
charge of conspiracy to defraud the now-defunct San Juan AIDS
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   He admitted that he received a $40,000 campaign donation from
Advanced Community Health Services, the company hired to administer
the agency. Electoral laws limit such donations to $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   ''Looking at it in retrospect, I wouldn't do it again,'' Rosario
Burgos said. ''I didn't realize what I was doing. When I realized,
I was scared.''
</P>
<P>
   He also admitted to receiving a salary from the institute, where
a position was created for him after he lost his re-election bid in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   Rosario Burgos turned state's witness and testified against
institute officials Yamil Kouri, Jorge Garib and Luis Dubon, who
were convicted of stealing $2.2 million in federal AIDS funds.
</P>
<P>
   The scandal rocked the island's government and forced Gov. Pedro
Rossello and former San Juan Mayor Hector Luis Acevedo to take the
stand to deny witnesses' allegations that they accepted part of the
stolen money. Neither was charged with any crime.
</P>
<P>
   During the trial, House of Representatives vice president Jose
Granados Navedo admitted he accepted $200,000 in cash campaign
donations from Garib, including $100,000 stuffed in a cardboard
box. He resigned from the legislature but has not been charged with
wrongdoing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
