<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lights Won't Cause Nearsightedness  </HEADLINE>
By WILLIAM McCALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's OK for parents to leave on the night light, according to a
pair of new studies that say the light won't make children
nearsighted.
</P>
<P>
   Two groups of researchers report in this week's journal Nature
that they were unable to duplicate the results of an earlier study
indicating children who sleep with a night light until age 2 are
three times more likely to develop nearsightedness, or myopia.
</P>
<P>
   ''The original report suggested that parents turn out the
lights,'' said Jane Gwiazda of the New England College of Optometry
in Boston. ''And now with two studies to the contrary, it's safe to
say parents can leave the lights on.''
</P>
<P>
   The two follow-up studies were done separately at the New
England College of Optometry and Ohio State University.
</P>
<P>
   The original study was done by scientists at the University of
Pennsylvania and the Children's Hospital of Philadelphia and was
published in Nature last May. It raised the possibility that too
much light during the first two years of life prompts the rapidly
developing eyes to grow excessively and throws them out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   The follow-up studies found no difference between the rate of
myopia for children who slept in the dark and those who slept with
a night light.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, the real explanation may be -- at least indirectly
-- heredity, the researchers said. Myopic parents are more likely to
have myopic children. And myopic parents may like to leave night
lights on so they can see better at night.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston group studied 213 people ranging in age from 2 to 24,
with a mean age of 11. It found that 20 percent of the children who
slept with night lights developed myopia, exactly the same
percentage as the youngsters who slept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   The Ohio State study, which involved 1,220 children with a
median age of 10, found the percentage of children who became
nearsighted after sleeping with a night light as babies was about
17 percent. Statistically, that was the same as the 20 percent of
the children who slept in the dark.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the percentage of children who slept in a fully lit
room and later became nearsighted was essentially the same at 22
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest link the Ohio State study found was between the
number of nearsighted parents and their use of night lights.
</P>
<P>
   ''Surprise, surprise: Those of us who can't see like to leave
the lights on,'' said Ohio State optometrist Karla Zadnik.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Richard Stone, an ophthalmologist and co-author of the
Pennsylvania study, said in a response published in Nature that
widespread publicity may have led parents in the follow-up studies
to underreport night light use out of guilt for possibly
contributing to myopia.
</P>
<P>
   Stone also said the differing results may be due to the
differing average age for the children -- the average age in the
Pennsylvania study was 8.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: New England College of Optometry site:
http://www.ne-optometry.edu
</P>
<P>
   Ohio State University site: http://www.optometry.ohio-state.edu
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0024 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Teen Funds Scholarship for Friend  </HEADLINE>
By JAY LINDSAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- For 12 years, David Glattstein felt he could have
done more for Matthew Kamin, his friend who died of leukemia at age
6.
</P>
<P>
   In Matthew's memory, Glattstein -- now 18 -- is using some of the
$20,000 he earned on the stock market to endow a college
scholarship at Swampscott High School.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000 scholarship will be awarded to a member of the
school's class of 2000, which graduates Sunday. Glattstein is a
graduating senior, and Matthew would have been, too.
</P>
<P>
   Glattstein endowed the Matthew J. Kamin Rainbow Scholarship
anonymously last year and only went public recently with prodding
from Matthew's grandfather, Harvey Michaels.
</P>
<P>
   ''What David is doing, I think is unheard of,'' Michaels said.
''It unselfish, it's magnanimous, it's genuine. It serves as a role
model for other people to give a little bit of themselves and give
something to society.''
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, Glattstein and his friend Matthew were in the
first grade in Swampscott, an upscale, seaside Boston suburb. Their
families were close. They shared a fascination with rainbows, which
is remembered in the scholarship name.
</P>
<P>
   Glattstein was too young to understand how sick Matthew was. He
just knew he wanted him to feel better. So he visited him in the
hospital, his favorite stuffed animal in tow as a gift. But by the
time Glattstein arrived, Matthew had died.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, Glattstein has lived with a lingering -- if unfounded
-- regret about Matthew's death.
</P>
<P>
   ''I always felt guilty that I didn't do enough to help him,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   By last spring, Glattstein realized he had the resources to
honor Matthew's memory, thanks to some savvy stock market
investing.
</P>
<P>
   Glattstein began investing at age 15, using money he received at
his bar mitzvah. He focused on high-tech companies, which he knew
were fueling the stock market boom, and his account grew from
$6,000 to $22,000.
</P>
<P>
   Swampscott High principal Peter Sack said he was touched when
Glattstein approached him last year about funding the annual
scholarship, but not entirely surprised. Glattstein, a member of
the Political Action Club and editor of the school newspaper,
struck the principal as extremely conscientious.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's an activist in the most positive sense of the word,''
Sack said.
</P>
<P>
   Finalists for the scholarship were chosen based on their answer
to this essay question: Define the meaning of living life to the
fullest. The winner, chosen by Glattstein and Matthew's
grandfather, will be announced at commencement Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Glattstein said he was looking for someone who understood that
people should give more than they take.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0149 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0025 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio Hits the Campaign Trail  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Newly nominated Republican Senate
candidate Rick Lazio set off across New York in his ''Mainstream
Express'' campaign bus, looking for votes in his battle against
Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The Long Island congressman pledged to take a ''message of hope,
opportunity and responsibility'' on the road after he was the
unanimous pick of his party's state convention to take on the first
lady in the closely watched Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With the ''Rocky'' theme blaring from loudspeakers and sporting
a fat lip courtesy of a tumble during a Memorial Day parade, Lazio
declared Tuesday that he is the underdog in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ''My opponent is better financed and better known. She comes to
New York with the support of every left-wing special interest, from
Washington insiders to the Hollywood elite,'' Lazio told more than
400 cheering delegates and 1,000 more in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   And, pressing a favorite Republican theme -- that Clinton is a
carpetbagger -- Lazio said, ''I have one advantage she'll never have
-- I can be myself. I am a New Yorker.''
</P>
<P>
   While not criticizing Clinton by name, Lazio accused ''the
opposition camp'' of practicing the ''politics of division ... It
is a bleak, angry place, built of fear. And I will not go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said the congressman
had ''offered the people of New York recycled insults and rhetoric
that doesn't match his record. Time and time again Rick Lazio has
voted against New York's working families in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ''Hillary Clinton has been running an inclusive campaign since
day one and fighting for children and families for thirty years,''
Wolfson added. ''New Yorkers will always be able to count on
Hillary to stand up for them in the Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio left the convention for a three-day bus trip across the
state in his customized cruiser dubbed ''The Mainstream Express''
by campaign aides who used to work on the presidential campaign of
Sen. John McCain. The senator's bus was called ''The Straight Talk
Express.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lazio, 42, the GOP nomination marked the culmination of a
dream that seemed dashed just nine months ago when Gov. George
Pataki persuaded him to suspend his fledgling Senate campaign in
favor of an expected run by New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor dropped out of the race this month after his
diagnosis with prostate cancer. Pataki and other Republican leaders
quickly rallied around the little-known Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has stressed his New York roots, a none-too-subtle
reminder that Clinton only moved into the state in January. And, he
has pointed to his record as a four-term congressman who helped
overhaul the nation's public housing system, worked to protect the
environment and voted to raise the minimum wage.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton camp, on the other hand, portrays Lazio as a
conservative out of step with mainstream New Yorkers. Clinton aides
have repeatedly pointed to Lazio's support for eight out of 10
proposals from former House Speaker Newt Gingrich's ''Contract with
America.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has also taken her rival to task for saying he's a
supporter of abortion rights, noting he has regularly voted to cut
federal Medicaid funding for poor women's abortions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton and Giuliani, Lazio has favors banning the
late-term procedure critics call ''partial-birth abortion.'' That
cleared the way for him to pick up the endorsement of the state's
Conservative Party. No Republican has won statewide office in New
York since 1974 without Conservative Party backing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0150 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
