<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pa. Relaxes Standards for Bar Exams  </HEADLINE>
By HOPE YEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Less than 10 years ago, prospective
lawyers breezed through the Pennsylvania bar exam at a rate law
students in neighboring states could only hope to equal.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania soon found itself with an image problem, seen as a
haven for litigators who couldn't qualify elsewhere. Standards were
raised in 1995, but the state Supreme Court has now decided to give
law students a break.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in July 2001, aspiring lawyers won't have to meet
individual scoring requirements on both the multiple-choice and
essay portions of the state bar exam. They will pass based on their
combined overall score.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our only concern is that the attorneys that are licensed have
the minimum competency requirements to practice law,'' said Mark
Dows of the Pennsylvania Board of Law Examiners. ''We did not want
to penalize those who take the multiple choice better than the
essay.''
</P>
<P>
   The changes will require Pennsylvania applicants to achieve a
combined score of at least 272 -- two points higher than the
combined total of the two minimum scores currently required. The
state is already adding a ''performance test,'' where test-takers
draft a memo analyzing the viability of a fictitious client's legal
claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's more worrisome for us,'' said Tracy Laskowski, a
third-year student at Villanova Law School. ''The fear is having
any change.''
</P>
<P>
   The requirements certainly have had their ups and downs.
</P>
<P>
   Until the mid-1990s, Pennsylvania was one of a few states which
did not grade the essay section if test-takers did well enough on
the multiple-choice questions. The pass rate was 84 percent,
compared with the 61 percent to 80 percent rate in neighboring
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''Pennsylvania had a reputation of being one of the easiest
places to take the bar,'' said Dale Larrimore, executive director
of Bar/Bri of Pennsylvania, which prepares law students for the
exam. ''The thought was that all the people taking the bar here
couldn't pass anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to dispel Pennsylvania's lackluster image in the legal
community, the state Supreme Court in 1995 instituted minimum
scores on both portions of the exam. Passing rates dipped to 48
percent in February 1995 before rebounding to 69 percent that July.
</P>
<P>
   The court had problems of its own at the time. One of its
justices, Rolf Larsen, faced accusations of abusing prescription
drugs and showing favoritism to lawyer friends. He was convicted of
federal conspiracy in 1994 and impeached by the General Assembly,
leading critics to call for legal reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Supreme Court finally decided to increase the standards to
help raise the reputation of Pennsylvania attorneys around the
country,'' Larrimore said.
</P>
<P>
   The proportion of attorneys inside Pennsylvania itself exceeds
the national average. One of every 218 Pennsylvanians is licensed
to practice law, compared to a one-to-295 ratio nationwide,
according to figures from the state Court of Judicial Discipline,
Census Bureau and U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,900 applicants are expected to take the state bar exam
in July, compared to 3,800 test-takers in 1994. The passage rate
today is about 70 percent -- low when compared to the 72 percent to
78 percent success rates in New Jersey, Maryland and New York,
which score their exams differently but are considered comparable
in difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers say they don't mind the constantly changing
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''With Philadelphia being the kind of place it is, there are
some practices where you are dealing with people barred in many
states with certain attitudes,'' said Lauren Levin, a Philadelphia
civil litigator. ''But the real test is not the bar exam -- it's
what kind of lawyer you are and how well you do.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania Board of Law Examiners: http://www.pable.org
</P>
<P>
   Bar/Bri Bar Review: http://www.barbri.com
</P>
</TEXT>
