<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Wins Full UN Representation  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- More than 50 years after Israel became a
member of the United Nations, it will finally get the chance to be
represented on key U.N. bodies in New York.
</P>
<P>
   For Israeli U.N. Ambassador Yehuda Lancry, acceptance in one of
the U.N. regional groups that decides on committee memberships
marks a turning point in the Jewish state's stormy relationship
with the United Nations and an end to decades of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   For U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke, it marks the end to a
grave injustice and a victory for the Clinton administration, which
decided to publicize a decades-old, behind-the-scenes campaign to
find a region that would accept Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Under U.N. rules, regional groups decide who fills the 10
rotating seats on the Security Council and other key U.N. committee
assignments. Israel was the only U.N. member that was not part of a
regional group, because Arab nations have repeatedly blocked its
admission to the Asian Group -- where it belongs geographically.
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, the U.N. regional group of European, North American
and other countries invited Israel to become a temporary member,
with some strings. On Tuesday, Lancry sent a formal letter of
acceptance to the Netherlands' U.N. Ambassador Peter van Walsum,
who currently heads the West European and Others Group, or WEOG, as
it is called.
</P>
<P>
   ''We consider that this is a historic turning point in our
relationship with the United Nations. It is really a new chapter
which we are opening with the family of nations,'' Lancry said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It isn't the end of the road,'' Holbrooke added, ''but it is
far and away the biggest step taken in the last four decades
towards putting Israel where it belongs, as absolutely a full
member of the U.N. without discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   Why, after years of opposition from several European countries,
was Israel finally admitted?
</P>
<P>
   Lancry said Israel started campaigning for membership in WEOG
after the 1993 Oslo accords, which laid the groundwork for the
current Middle East peace process, but without success.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after Kofi Annan became secretary-general in January 1997,
he raised the issue of Israel's exclusion. On a visit to the Middle
East in March 1998, he said, ''this anomaly should be corrected,''
insisting that the equality of all states be upheld.
</P>
<P>
   Lancry credited Annan's ''exceptional courage'' and Holbrooke's
formidable diplomatic skills in expressing the Clinton
administration's determination ''to put an end to this longstanding
inequity.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing alongside Lancry at a news conference, Holbrooke said
there was a window of opportunity -- and the Clinton administration
worked closely with Israel's President Ehud Barak and Lancry to act
while it was open.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he said, Clinton, Vice President Al Gore and
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright repeatedly raised the issue
with key leaders, ''and one by one the obstacles began to fall
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the deal, Israel must keep pressing for membership in the
Asian group and WEOG will reconsider its temporary membership in
four years.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is also barred from submitting candidates for any
contested posts for two years, and must accept WEOG's existing
rotation for U.N. posts.
</P>
<P>
   ''For Israel simply to go to the head of the line in year one
would not have been reasonable,'' Holbrooke explained.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.-Israeli campaign will continue because Israel is only
invited to join WEOG in New York -- not in Geneva, Vienna and
Nairobi where the United Nations also operates.
</P>
<P>
   But Holbrooke stressed that ''New York is the mothership'' of
U.N. operations and Israel's acceptance by WEOG here was the
critical hurdle.
</P>
<P>
   Lancry said he does not expect Israel to get a seat on the
Security Council in the next 10 years -- but he does see some
benefits in WEOG membership here.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that it permits Israel now to channel its energy, its
activity, its spirit, to take advantage of the family of nations --
and to give something to the family of nations,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
