<DOCNO> APW20000531.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leftist Has Mexico City Race Lead  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Candidates for the mayoral race in the
Western Hemisphere's largest city squared off in a televised
debate, but a leftist leader was already the heavy favorite to win
the July 2 election.
</P>
<P>
   Andres Manuel Lopez Obrador of the Democratic Revolution Party
leads his nearest rival by 17 percentage points in the latest poll,
and one minor party candidate essentially conceded during the
debate Tuesday night that Lopez Obrador would win, asking him to
form an inclusive government.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez Obrador pledged to increase funding for education, combat
both the causes and symptoms of crime, and make the government more
humble.
</P>
<P>
   ''We propose to govern this city from the bottom up,'' he said.
''There won't be luxury offices. We will lower the salaries of
high-level public servants. We won't buy late-model vehicles. We
won't use bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   ''We can't have a rich government and a poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   The two other main candidates, the ruling party's Jesus
Silva-Herzog and the center-right National Action Party's Santiago
Creel, spent most of their time criticizing the current, 3-year-old
administration of the city, which is of Lopez Obrador's party.
</P>
<P>
   Silva-Herzog, whose party ran Mexico City by presidential
appointment from 1929 until 1997, said in the three years since
Democratic Revolution took over, the government has built only 203
houses. He pledged to build 100,000 over his six-year term.
</P>
<P>
   He blamed the current government for crime, corruption and
constant demonstrations that clog traffic -- all problems that were
at least as bad during his own party's rule of the city.
</P>
<P>
   ''This city is sick, very sick, and needs emergency care,'' he
said. ''Our city needs to put order into the disorder in which we
live.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Creel: ''We work day and night here. We have a city that
never stops. And we have a government that is practically lying
down. On July 2, do we want more of the 70 years of ruling-party
corruption or of the 1,000 days of Democratic Revolution
incompetence?''
</P>
<P>
   Mexico City, with close to 9 million people within city limits
and another 10 million just outside, is the political, financial
and cultural heart of this highly centralized country, and the
mayor wields significant power.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Revolution's Cuauhtemoc Cardenas won a stunning
landslide in 1997 when the mayorship was put up for election for
the first time, but resigned last September to run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cardenas had limited success in creating the
large-scale changes he had promised, his interim successor, Rosario
Robles, has been popular.
</P>
<P>
   That appears to have helped Lopez Obrador, who has surged in the
polls since the campaigning began early in the year.
</P>
<P>
   A poll published Tuesday in the newspaper Reforma showed 44
percent of respondents planned to vote for Lopez Obrador, compared
with 27 percent each for Silva Herzog, Mexico's former ambassador
to the United States, and Creel, a former congressional leader.
</P>
<P>
   Reforma conducted face-to-face interviews with 1,109 people May
19-21. The poll had a margin of error of 3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The elections for president, congress and many local posts will
be held July 2. National Action's presidential candidate, Vicente
Fox, is running generally even in the polls with ruling-party
candidate Francisco Labastida.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
