<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inauguration Protest Urged in Peru  </HEADLINE>
By MONTE HAYES
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Defeated opposition candidate Alejandro Toledo
is calling for a march of four million protesters in Lima to block
President Alberto Fujimori's inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after a runoff vote boycotted by Toledo and marred by
clashes between demonstrators and police, the former World Bank
consultant said the street protests that have gone on throughout
this Andean nation would continue and build into one massive march
designed to paralyze Lima.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo told foreign journalists Tuesday that the protest is
scheduled for July 26, two days before the presidential
inauguration, ''if Fujimori is still around on that date.''
</P>
<P>
   International criticism of Fujimori continues to grow outside
Peru. However, the Clinton administration backpedaled Tuesday from
its official statement a day earlier that Fujimori could not
''claim legitimacy'' after Sunday's ''flawed'' election. State
Department spokesman Philip Reeker limited himself to an expression
of deep regret.
</P>
<P>
   But U.S. officials also said Washington is expected to loosen
official ties with Peru. A State Department official said the
administration was reviewing its policies toward Peru in
international lending organizations.
</P>
<P>
   He said the United States was awaiting today's meeting of the
Organization of American States permanent council before deciding
on future steps.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff was abandoned by independent monitors who deemed the
process unfair.
</P>
<P>
   In a brief nationwide television address Monday night, Fujimori
reiterated that the election was fair and said he hoped he would
not disappoint Peruvians ''in initiating a more authentic
democracy'' in his next five years in power.
</P>
<P>
   But Toledo called Fujimori a dictator who was fraudulently
re-elected and spelled out a three-pronged strategy to keep the
president from extending his stay in power for a third, five-year
term.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he would travel the country to prepare for the
march, speaking with university students, unions and other
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Another way Toledo said he plans to keep Fujimori from being
sworn in is by persuading at least 61 of the 120 members of
Congress to boycott the body's opening session on July 28. He said
Fujimori cannot be sworn in without a majority present in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori's supporters won only 52 seats in the new Congress, but
Toledo charged that Fujimori's political allies have begun offering
as much as $50,000 to some of the congressmen elected on Toledo's
ticket to get them to join Fujimori's governing alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ''They want to reach 61 or 62 so they will have a majority,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he also planned to dispatch representatives to
Washington, Europe and other Latin American nations ''to explain
our position and the need to annul this election.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal, he said, was to have a new, clean election called and
if necessary seek a ''transition government'' in the interim. He
said that would require Fujimori to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said he still hoped that the OAS will condemn Fujimori's
government as illegitimate but said he realizes it may be difficult
for the member nations to reach a consensus.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
