<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Missile Defense System Criticized  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY ULBRICH
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The United States has put on the hard
sell for more than a year now, but the European allies remain far
from convinced that Washington's proposed new national missile
defense system is wise or necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and China don't like it, either.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, it's not even certain the thing will even work.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, who meets with EU leaders Wednesday before
traveling to Moscow for his first face-to-face talks with President
Vladimir Putin of Russia, is scheduled to decide this year whether
to order the system deployed. It would entail a small number of
interceptors that are supposed to knock down incoming nuclear
missiles fired countries, newly armed with nuclear weapons, that
the United States considers ''rogue states.''
</P>
<P>
   The greatest worry in Europe is that the missile defense system
would end the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty, deal a blow to
efforts to prevent proliferation of nuclear weapons and relaunch
the arms race at a time when most the world wants rid of nukes.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, President Jacques Chirac of France voiced the fears
of many Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   ''How do you convince (nations) to stop piling up new arms when
more powerful countries say it's necessary to develop technologies
that put hard-won strategic balances into question?'' Chirac said.
</P>
<P>
   Washington says with countries like North Korea and Iran,
possibly Iraq and others, acquiring nuclear technology, new dangers
arise. Nuclear dissuasion may not prevent these countries from
launching missiles, the Americans say, so a limited defense system
is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ballistic missile threat from states of concern is growing
and real,'' Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told the allies
last week at a meeting of NATO foreign ministers in Florence,
Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed U.S. system would be illegal under the existing ABM
treaty, which prohibits nationwide missile defenses. The United
States wants to renegotiate the treaty with Russia to take the new
threats into account.
</P>
<P>
   ''But even the modernization, as the Americans say, of the
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty will lead to extremely dangerous and
unpredictable tendencies,'' Sergei Ivanov, secretary of Russia's
Security Council, said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has sent to Europe a steady stream of top-ranking
officials of the State and Defense departments to brief both Russia
and the allies on threats as the Americans see them. This has been
reinforced by teams of experts explaining details of current plans
the national missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   A final test of the interceptors is scheduled for July. Clinton
is expected to make a decision in the autumn whether to go ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ''President Clinton's decision will take into account cost,
threat, technological feasibility and a range of other national
security factors, including the impact on our relations with our
NATO and Pacific allies as well as Russia and China,'' Albright
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the allies know that no matter what their
objections, the decision is an internal American matter.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are asking Clinton to reflect before his decision on the
repercussions of NMD on the entire world system,'' Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine of France said at the Florence meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Some allies, like Germany, would like to see the system deployed
as part of an overall package that would include a big step toward
a START III nuclear weapons agreement, a modified ABM treaty and
agreement with the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have to take care that the ABM treaty is not going to be
substantially damaged and that the international arms control
regime will be strengthened,'' said German Foreign Minister Joschka
Fischer. ''It's clearly a decision for the United States, but it
will not be taken in a foreign policy-free environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0205 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Leaves Bush Attacks to Others  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- As advertised, a softer, sweeter Al Gore showed
up to accept the endorsement of the League of Conservation Voters.
</P>
<P>
   Gone were descriptions of his opponent as ''smug'' and
''arrogant,'' which left Republican presidential rival George W.
Bush to grouse about the campaign's sudden role reversal.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know how many times you're able to reinvent yourself
in the course of a campaign,'' Bush said Tuesday about Gore's
nascent strategy of playing nice guy while leaving Democratic
surrogates to do the dirty work of trying to bring down the Texas
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Denver, Bush, who has earned positive headlines
laying out his policy agenda, slammed the Clinton-Gore
administration's management of the military and said Gore is
unqualified for promotion to commander in chief. President
Clinton's former Veterans Affairs Secretary Jesse Brown, in turn,
led a conference call with reporters to question why Bush curtailed
his 1970s tour with the Texas Air National Guard, which kept him
out of Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett accused Gore of ''hiding
behind surrogates to pollute Bush's record.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign schedule reflects the bait-and-switch attempt to
highlight the personal stories of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Gore and his wife Tipper appear at a suburban Washington
community center to discuss mental health, with which Mrs. Gore has
struggled, and an initiative to help parents get insurance and care
for troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday in Atlanta, he speaks out for the privacy and
treatment rights of people with cancer, which killed his older
sister in 1984. Friday's topic, in Washington, is fatherhood. On
Memorial Day, he told veterans about his decision to enlist in the
Army and volunteer for duty in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Playing up the personal, however, has seemed more a product of
Gore's speechwriters than his own heart. His talk of Vietnam was
brief and stilted. And, to Wisconsin environmentalists, Gore
breezed over what aides had billed as a major focus of the speech:
how he learned environmentalism on his father's farm and at his
mother's dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   The light touch is a marked departure for the candidate who, for
weeks, has hammered Bush as smug, arrogant, reckless and
irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign officials eyeing the polls have worried, of late, that
the attacks could backfire and turn off voters, particularly women,
and so Gore has increasingly turned to surrogates -- including
President Clinton and Cabinet secretaries Donna Shalala, Andrew
Cuomo and William Cohen -- to lob the direct criticisms at Bush. In
a recent interview on National Public Radio, Clinton attacked the
Texas governor's national security, environmental and economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush generally has let others criticize Gore on his behalf. But
on the issue of military readiness, he went after Gore himself on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Chris Lehane called the switch part of
''the certain rhythms to every campaign'' and suggested Gore would
not hold his tongue permanently. ''There will be plenty of
opportunities to draw comparisons and contrasts as we go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   This shift in strategy is the latest for Gore. In a dramatic
move last fall, he moved his campaign headquarters from Washington
to Nashville, Tenn., shed some of the trappings of the office of
vice president and began holding lengthy town hall-style meetings
to better connect with voters.
</P>
<P>
   At Tuesday's lakefront campaign appearance showcasing his long
history of environmentalism, Gore managed 22 minutes of lunchtime
remarks without a single reference -- veiled, indirect or otherwise
-- to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane had told reporters to expect the kid gloves, saying Gore
would focus ''on the importance of the environment to families''
and leave discussion of ''the mess in Texas'' to the League of
Conservation Voters. Lehane himself was unable to resist ribbing
Bush, using the phrase ''the mess in Texas'' four times in five
minutes to describe Bush's record.
</P>
<P>
   The program at Milwaukee's War Memorial Center played out
exactly as billed, with League president Deb Callahan harshly
taking after Bush while the closest Gore got to criticism of anyone
was a reference to ''pro-pollution forces in Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Even in a round of interviews with Wisconsin TV stations, Gore
mentioned the Texas governor's name only once. Referencing his own
support for campaign finance reform, Gore said simply: ''Governor
Bush is opposed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   On the economy, Gore blandly told Madison's WKOW-TV, ''My
opponent's approach is very different.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0206 </TRAILER>
