<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Club Member Criticizes Gore  </HEADLINE>
By PETE YOST
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A pioneer in the environmental movement has
joined a board member of the Sierra Club in criticizing Vice
President Al Gore's ''tawdry environmental record.''
</P>
<P>
   David Brower, the club's executive director in the 1950s and
1960s, said Tuesday that when he resigned from the board earlier
this month he urged ''that they support Ralph Nader.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The other two (presidential) candidates are really the same
color'' on environmental issues and ''it's too bad,'' the
87-year-old Brower said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   His comments followed the Republican National Committee's
release Tuesday of a 6-month-old internal e-mail by Sierra Club
board member Michael Dorsey, a doctoral candidate at the University
of Michigan's school of natural resources and environment.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsey's memo said that over the past seven years, the nation's
natural resources ''have been held hostage to the highest bidder,
especially by the oil companies.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Gore was a major disappointment and I agree with Michael''
Dorsey, Brower said. He added that he was ''quite pleased'' when
the environmental group 'Friends of the Earth' ''took off after the
vice president and backed Bill Bradley instead'' last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Gore came under attack, he was endorsed Tuesday by the
League of Conservation Voters, the political arm of the
environmental movement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign shrugged off Dorsey's e-mail as old news and the
Sierra Club issued a statement applauding the vice president's
''vision.'' The group, which says it is surveying members before
endorsing a candidate, is airing $250,000 worth of ads criticizing
Republican presidential candidate Gov. George W. Bush's
environmental record in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact is Al Gore has helped make this administration one of
the most pro-environment in a generation,'' spokesman Doug Hattaway
said. ''He is far and away the best candidate to protect our air
and water while we maintain economic growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Nader, a Green Party presidential hopeful, tried to capitalize
on the uneasiness among some environmentalists about Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no difference between Gore and Bush except their
rhetoric'' and Republicans and Democrats are ''two parties who
belong to Big Money,'' Nader told CNN. ''Look at the actual record
of the Clinton-Gore administration. They've broken all kinds of
promises that were in Al Gore's 1992 book.''
</P>
<P>
   Released as Gore was switching from a Senate career to
presidential politics as Bill Clinton's running mate, Gore's book
''Earth in the Balance'' turned into a hot seller and cemented his
reputation as an environmentalist with a world view.
</P>
<P>
   In a play on the title, Dorsey's four-page memo says that
''Under the Vice President's leadership the Earth has never been in
the Balance.''
</P>
<P>
   In the memo, which referred to the group's internal
deliberations, Dorsey claimed that Gore failed to protect the
environment on issues ranging from the Florida Everglades to global
free-trade agreements.
</P>
<P>
   ''With this legacy, no real environmentalist could ever endorse
Al Gore,'' said Dorsey's memo, captioned, ''The Top 10 Reasons Why
Environmentalists &AMP; We Directors of the Sierra Club Should 'Not'
Endorse Vice President Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   His e-mail suggests the board was wrestling with endorsing the
vice president as early as last November, when Gore was battling a
primary challenge from Democrat Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were unable to come to any conclusion as to whether we
would support the vice president -- either in the primaries or the
general election. The chair of the political committee asked that
directors share information on the environmental records of the
candidates,'' Dorsey wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have amassed some information'' and ''although what follows
is a damning indictment of the vice president's tawdry
environmental record, it unfortunately represents only the tip of
the iceberg,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, talked tough on the environment Tuesday,
pledging in words reminiscent of former President Bush's 1992
no-new-taxes promise that he would be unyielding in his protection
of national parks and forests.
</P>
<P>
   ''And just so I'm crystal clear about it: No new road building
and no timber sales in the roadless areas of our national
forests,'' he said in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   On Alaska, Gore was similarly firm. ''I will never -- I will
never agree to oil drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife
(Refuge), never,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0208 </TRAILER>
