<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Takes Aim at Gore on Military  </HEADLINE>
By GLEN JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) -- Stepping out from John McCain's shadow,
George W. Bush is leading a Republican charge against the
Clinton-Gore record on military matters.
</P>
<P>
   He was launching a second day of attacks today at the New Mexico
Veterans Memorial Park.
</P>
<P>
   During the GOP presidential primaries, McCain, the senior U.S.
senator from Arizona and a former Vietnam prisoner of war,
chastised the administration for overdeploying troops and allowing
some to live on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   From New Mexico, Bush was heading to Arizona for two
fund-raisers. He also was appearing with McCain's colleague, Sen.
John Kyl, but not with McCain, who endorsed Bush on May 9 in
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday in Colorado, the first stop on his four-day,
five-state Western swing, Bush accused the Clinton-Gore
administration of letting the U.S. military decay. He said low
morale and lax troop readiness disqualify the vice president from
promotion to commander in chief.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Clinton-Gore record cries out for a new sign on the
Pentagon. It says, 'Under new management,''' the Republican
presidential contender said during a stop at the 100-year-old VFW
Post No. 1, the nation's oldest Veterans of Foreign Wars club.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with his new strategy of being less harsh, Gore did
not respond directly to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, a surrogate, former Veterans Affairs Secretary Jesse
Brown, raised the issue of Bush being allowed to adjust his
commitment to the Texas Air National Guard in 1972 and 1973 while
working in Alabama on a Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is an issue that he must explain to the American
people,'' said Brown, who was VA chief from 1993 to 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer replied: ''Mr. Brown must be
unaware of the fact that the governor fulfilled all his
requirements, which is why he was honorably discharged from the
Guard. It's unfortunate that the vice president is hiding behind a
surrogate to make unfounded personal attacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Citing reports that two of 10 Army divisions were not at the
highest state of readiness, that the Air Force ended last year
short 1,200 pilots and that 6,000 soldiers are on food stamps, Bush
said: ''Al Gore claims that qualifies him for a promotion. No.''
</P>
<P>
   He also rejected an offer from Defense Secretary William Cohen,
a fellow Republican, for a briefing on nuclear security. Cohen made
the offer Sunday after Bush proposed deep cuts in the nation's
missile stockpile.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the briefing I got from Colin Powell and Dick Cheney
and Henry Kissinger was substantial,'' Bush said at a news
conference, referring to members of his foreign policy team. ''I
call on my opponent not to allow the administration to politicize
matters of defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Kenneth Bacon, asked if the Bush campaign had
responded to Cohen's invitation, said, ''The only response we've
seen is in the press, and that was, they said they didn't need such
a briefing. So the secretary considers the issue finished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
