<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Belfour Does Belly Flop for Stars  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Dallas Stars goaltender Ed Belfour
seemed to be in a daze in Game 1 of the Stanley Cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, he was.
</P>
<P>
   Belfour, the biggest Star of them all as Dallas won the Stanley
Cup last season, clearly wasn't himself as the favored Stars were
embarrassed by the New Jersey Devils 7-3 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just that the Devils kept scoring and scoring, it was
how they scored. With soft shots from the point, with
knuckleball-like shots that floated between Belfour's pads, with
shots off the sticks of players -- namely, defenseman Ken Daneyko --
who hadn't scored in the playoffs in five years.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't the Belfour who outplayed the game's premier goalie,
Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, in leading the Stars to their first
Stanley Cup title a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   No, this was the pre-Stanley Cup Belfour -- the sometimes
confused, unconfident Belfour whose unsteadiness was seen as the
Stars' biggest liability going into last season's finals.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eddie didn't have a great night,'' coach Ken Hitchcock said.
''He has had great nights for us the whole playoffs. He didn't have
a great one, but I know he will bounce back.''
</P>
<P>
   A bad night? This was a bad month for Belfour, who brought a
1.81 goals-against average into the finals. In the previous round,
Belfour limited the Colorado Avalanche to 13 goals, the fewest in a
seven-game Stanley Cup semifinal series in a half-century.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars seemingly didn't have an excuse for their performance,
but Belfour did. He developed a cold during the Western finals, and
took antibiotics and decongestants to get him through Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   ''It affected my judgment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When did he realize it?
</P>
<P>
   ''After they scored six goals,'' Belfour said.
</P>
<P>
   Devils fans delighted in Belfour's misfortune, serenading him
with the chant of ''Ed-die, Ed-die,'' before he was mercifully
lifted early in the third period. They also chanted, ''Marty's
Better,'' referring to Devils goaltender Martin Brodeur.
</P>
<P>
   The chants were a derisive reference to the ''Eddie's Better''
cheers that Stars fans recited against Colorado. Before that
series, Belfour said he was ''as good or better'' than Avalanche
goaltender Patrick Roy.
</P>
<P>
   On this forgettable night, Belfour couldn't have played much
worse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they played a pretty good offensive game and I
definitely wasn't on my game, making the stops I should be
making,'' said Belfour, who stopped only 12 of 18 shots. ''I didn't
have much energy out there for myself and I don't think our team
played with a lot of energy, either.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour expects to feel better, and play better, in Game 2
Thursday. If he doesn't, the Stars risk going back to Dallas down
2-0 in a series they were favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he will bounce back,'' Hitchcock said.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, it was difficult to predict how Belfour would react
to adversity, and his teammates knew it. That all changed when the
Stars won the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think Eddie has bad games,'' Stars forward Mike Keane
said. ''We didn't help him very much. Ed Belfour is not due for a
bad game. We have to play better in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Belfour also plans to lay off the cold medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm definitely going to come to the rink with the attitude to
play a lot better and make those saves, and try and play the best
game I can,'' Belfour said. ''It's just one game and definitely a
wake-up call for all of us. We have to play a lot better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0221 </TRAILER>
