<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Polish President Talks With the AP  </HEADLINE>
By DINA KRAFT
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Poland's visiting president said Jewish
families whose property was seized after World War II would be
compensated if Poland lifts legal barriers.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press, Polish President
Alexander Kwasniewski said Tuesday that if the Polish government
legalizes privatization of property seized by the communists, then
Jews and others would be at least partially compensated for
property lost.
</P>
<P>
   Most Jewish property was first seized by the Nazis during World
War II, then taken over by the communist government.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we have such a law, of course we will try to give some
recompensation,'' Kwasniewski said, ''This of course means for
Jewish people, Jewish families too.''
</P>
<P>
   The president, who is in Israel for a three-day visit, said he
discussed the matter during meetings at Israel's parliament Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Kwasniewski said Jewish compensation was taking time because
Poland's borders were dramatically changed by World War II, making
privatization complicated.
</P>
<P>
   Some 3.5 million Jews made up a thriving community in Poland
before World War II. About 3 million were killed in Nazi death
camps and ghettos, and others left Poland in the 1960s amid
communist-sponsored anti-Semitic campaigns. The community now
numbers 20,000.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli-Polish relations have also been strained by the presence
of a large cross next to the Auschwitz death camp, where 1 million
Jews were killed. About 300 smaller crosses on the site were
removed last May.
</P>
<P>
   Noting Pope John Paul II's recent pilgrimage to the Holy Land,
which was heralded as a milestone in Jewish-Catholic relations,
Kwasniewski said now was a good time to again address the cross.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a good time to discuss with the Catholic church how to
find a solution without humiliating anybody,'' Kwasniewski said.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of the cross, which was originally erected as a
backdrop for a 1979 papal mass, has drawn protests from Jewish
groups around the world and the Israeli government for insulting
the memory of Jews killed at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   During his visit, Kwasniewski met with Israeli President Ezer
Weizman and Prime Minister Ehud Barak.
</P>
<P>
   Kwasniewski, on his second official trip to Israel, was to
discuss ways to boost Poland's annual $40 million exports to Israel
and encourage more Israeli investment in Poland, as well as
cooperation between Polish and Israeli arms industries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0224 </TRAILER>
