<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 06:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Upholds Ban on Soft Money  </HEADLINE>
By HOPE YEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) -- Lawyers for a man challenging a 1907 ban
on corporate contributions to federal candidates say they may
appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court after a lower court upheld the law
as constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney Floyd Abrams had urged the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals to strike down the ban, arguing that ''soft money''
loopholes in the campaign finance law makes the ban on corporate
contributions ineffective.
</P>
<P>
   But in an unanimous opinion released this month, the 10-member
court in Philadelphia stated that ''any reform in this area must be
sought from Congress.''
</P>
<P>
   Abrams represents Renato P. Mariani, the former president of
Empire Sanitary Landfill who was indicted in a campaign finance
probe.
</P>
<P>
   Mariani and other former Empire officials were charged with
funneling corporate money from the landfill to candidates for
federal office, including President Clinton and Republican
presidential candidate Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   Mariani sued the federal government, contending the 93-year-old
contributions ban is unconstitutional. His attorneys also argued
the ban was meaningless since corporations may donate unlimited
amounts of soft money for so-called ''issue ads'' that make veiled
attacks on candidates without directly advocating their defeat.
</P>
<P>
   Abrams on Tuesday criticized the appeals court for upholding ''a
system which simply fails to accomplish anything other than trap an
occasional unwary contributor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Election Commission, which opposed Mariani's
challenge, said it was confident the ban could withstand an appeal
to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   General Counsel Lawrence Noble said that while the growing
influence of soft money is troubling, that was no reason to throw
out the regulations altogether.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just because the law doesn't address every perceived problem
doesn't mean it's unconstitutional,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 0651 </TRAILER>
