<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 10:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Down 22; Dow Down 15  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly lower at the start of
trading today as investors stepped back from Tuesday's buying spree
to re-evaluate their strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq
composite index was down 22.41 at 3,437.07. On Tuesday, the index
recorded its best day in history, with the largest percentage gain
ever and the second-largest point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators, which joined the Nasdaq in Tuesday's
rally, were also lower. The Dow Jones industrial average was down
14.65 at 10,512.48 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down
1.32 at 1,421.13.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies fell 1 9/16 to 56 7/16. The company, the
world's biggest maker of telephone equipment, is acquiring
Chromatis Networks, a privately held optical networking firm, for
about $4.5 billion in stock. Lucent said the deal would will help
it gain business in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart rose 11/16 to 8 5/16. The company tapped the No. 2
executive at drug chain CVS Corp. as its new leader, replacing
Floyd Hall, who announced in mid-May that he was planning to retire
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street is already waiting for the government's employment
report for the month of May, due out Friday. The report could offer
some indication of whether six interest rate increases by the
Federal Reserve have begun to slow the pace of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   But a preliminary sign of success came today from the Commerce
Department, which reported that sales of new homes tumbled 5.8
percent in April. That marked the largest decline since last
September.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 110.39 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies slipped 0.54 to
476.16.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's Xetra DAX index was up 0.02 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.05 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
