<HEADLINE> 'Sex and the City' Set To Return  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- As we rejoin ''Sex and the City,'' we find our
four gal pals, fabulous but chilly, at the railing of a ferry bound
for Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   ''Well, this is good,'' Miranda grumbles to the others. ''We're
actually crossing water to meet men.''
</P>
<P>
   She gazes back across the harbor at Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   ''Who would have thought,'' she deadpans, ''that an island that
tiny would be big enough to hold all our old boyfriends?''
</P>
<P>
   Setting sail for its third season on HBO Sunday at 9 p.m.
Eastern, ''Sex and the City'' retains all the sass, savvy and eye
appeal of summers past. For the next 18 weeks, we'll be treated to
the Manhattan mating dance. And showing us the steps will be four
of its funniest, most footloose devotees.
</P>
<P>
   There's Carrie (played by Sarah Jessica Parker), the
self-described ''sexual anthropologist'' who writes a newspaper
column called ''Sex and the City.'' Charlotte (Kristin Davis) is an
art dealer and Smith graduate who still believes in love, all the
better on Egyptian cotton sheets. Samantha (Kim Cattrall) is a
liberated PR exec who's been there, done that -- then done it again
elsewhere at her earliest opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out this sexy sisterhood is Cynthia Nixon as Miranda, a
corporate lawyer who, as self-fulfilling prophecies go, could beat
the Oracle at Delphi. That is, Miranda insists all men are scum
and, as often as not, manages to prove herself correct.
</P>
<P>
   Smart, cynical, judgmental and controlling -- that's Miranda.
''But the people who are prickliest are always softies on the
inside,'' Nixon insists. ''First, Miranda fights. Then she
softens.''
</P>
<P>
   And, often, with a splat. Like the time a bedmate overcame
Miranda's resistance to swearing at him while they made love. To
her surprise, she found she liked it. Then she went too far. She
shocked him with her outbursts. Another ex-boyfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about ''Sex and the City'' with a reporter recently,
Nixon is as tickled as anyone at such misadventures. And no wonder:
She escaped the unforgiving world her series depicts.
</P>
<P>
   ''People always ask me whether women really act that way,'' she
says. ''I don't! But I haven't been in the dating scene, like,
ever.''
</P>
<P>
   At 34, she has lived with her partner Daniel Mozes (a college
English professor and photographer) since she was 21. They have a
3{-year-old daughter, Samantha.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nixon thinks there's room on TV for a series about single
women with active libidos who aren't discredited as ''loose.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the greatest thing about the show, in terms of whether
it's 'real' or not, is the number of men these women have. As
viewers, we know them and love them, and we don't think of them as
sluts. They're just women who have a lot of sex.''
</P>
<P>
   And when they're not having it, they're liable to be talking
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ''On an upcoming episode they speculate on who among them they
might like to have a threesome with,'' says Nixon, chuckling.
''Nobody picks Miranda. None of the others even notice they haven't
picked her. So Miranda becomes obsessed with why.''
</P>
<P>
   Over a salad at a no-glitz restaurant near her Upper West Side
Manhattan digs, Nixon looks as different from her character as she
claims to be. While Miranda, like her three pals, is typically
glammed up, Nixon presents herself in jeans and a sweater over a
T-shirt. Her carrot-colored hair is capping a face free of makeup.
</P>
<P>
   Having just shopped for dinner, she has a sack of fresh produce
on the seat beside her. This is a welcome day off from the show's
busy routine, and she's making the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   ''I lead a very stable life,'' she says. ''I grew up here, and
my life is pretty much the same as it's always been.''
</P>
<P>
   Since childhood, part of that life has been acting. But only
part.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never felt like show biz was the be-all and end-all,'' she
explains. ''And when I was a child, everybody put the fear of God
in me that not many child actors become adult actors.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound advice. Yet Nixon made the leap and has been busy ever
since. Her films include ''The Pelican Brief'' and ''Addams Family
Values.'' She has appeared on and off Broadway in plays ranging
from ''Romeo and Juliet'' to ''Angels in America.'' She has had
numerous roles on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Auditions for ''Sex and the City'' came up in 1997. Nixon was
game for any of the four characters. Since then, she has thought a
lot about the ''in'' group they comprise.
</P>
<P>
   ''I see Carrie's friends as aspects of her,'' Nixon says. ''Her
body, Samantha. Her mind, Miranda. Her heart, Charlotte.''
</P>
<P>
   Then she proposes a distaff variation of the Judgment of Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want Carrie to have a dream where she goes back to ancient
Greece, and there's a contest between goddesses: Hera offers her
power, Athena offers her brains, Aphrodite offers her love.
</P>
<P>
   ''Samantha, Miranda and Charlotte would play the goddesses, each
arguing for their point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubtless, over a nice lunch. And no men allowed.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   HBO home page: http://www.hbo.com
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ....
</P>
<P>
   AMAZING: A powerful explosion rocks a large ship, throwing a man
overboard. Firemen battle a roaring blaze at a fireworks factory as
fireworks burst from the building. A motorcycle racer slams into a
wall and cartwheels over the railing. Two horses collide at a local
rodeo, sending both horses and the cowboys soaring into the air.
These are some of this week's real-life stories of courage and
survival, caught on tape for your voyeuristic pleasure. ''World's
Most Amazing Videos'' airs Saturday at 10 p.m. Eastern on NBC.
</P>
