<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Did Doctor Give Comfort or Death?  </HEADLINE>
By C.G. WALLACE
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Dr. Robert Weitzel was either an angel of
mercy, easing the pain of his dying patients, or a methodical
killer preying on the elderly patients entrusted to his care.
</P>
<P>
   Over 16 days from late 1995 to early 1996, five of the
psychiatrist's patients died at the geriatric-psychiatric unit of
the Davis Hospital and Medical Center in Layton.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend that all five were admitted for dementia --
not life threatening diseases -- and that Weitzel killed them with
lethal doses of morphine.
</P>
<P>
   Now the 43-year-old doctor is charged with five counts of murder
and could spend the rest of his life in prison if convicted. His
trial begins June 5 in Farmington.
</P>
<P>
   Weitzel's notes state he ordered nine nurses to administer
morphine to the patients. In some cases, he consulted with the
patients' families about making their loved ones more comfortable
as they died.
</P>
<P>
   At least four patients or their relatives had signed
do-not-resuscitate orders. The relatives trusted the doctor and
believed their family members had died natural deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Bringhurst, a registered nurse, described the day her
mother, 72-year-old Mary Crane, died.
</P>
<P>
   ''I asked if there was anything we could do,'' Bringhurst
testified at a preliminary hearing in late January. ''Dr. Weitzel
said, 'We can give her some morphine and keep her comfortable and
hasten the inevitable.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bringhurst thanked the doctor for his help.
</P>
<P>
   Merlin Larsen said at the hearing that he placed his 93-year-old
mother, Judith Larsen, who had suffered two strokes, at the
hospital after she began causing disturbances at a care center.
</P>
<P>
   Soon after she was comatose and Weitzel said she didn't have
long to live, Larsen said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was, I thought, very kindly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators exhumed the bodies of Larsen and Crane, along with
83-year-old Ennis Alldredge. Autopsies showed that Larsen died from
lethal amounts of morphine, police said. The cause of death was
inconclusive for Crane and Alldredge.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the bodies of Ellen Anderson, 91, and Lydia Smith,
90, were also exhumed. Those autopsy results have not been
returned.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys from both sides are honoring a gag order imposed at
the preliminary hearing and would not discuss the case.
</P>
<P>
   But evidence at that hearing showed that one of the five
patients died after just 17 hours in Weitzel's care. None of the
deceased was taking any medication stronger than Tylenol prior to
being admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know the doctor say the charges are absurd.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is truly going to break my heart if he is convicted. People
do not realize what a good doctor he is. He saved my daughter, what
more can I say?'' said Jan Smith LaBard, who credits Weitzel with
helping her teen-age daughter recover from severe depression.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Lubsen, who has known Weitzel for years, describes him as
a loyal friend who would lend support in times of need.
</P>
<P>
   Weitzel surrendered his license to practice medicine in
California in 1997 after allegedly having an affair with a former
patient he had treated for depression.
</P>
<P>
   At about that same time, the Utah Division of Occupational and
Professional Licensing began investigating an anonymous complaint
of misconduct in Utah, said division spokesman Kim Morris. The
licensing division turned over the contents of their investigation
to the police, Morris said. The murder charges followed.
</P>
<P>
   Weitzel also faces federal charges in Utah on 22 counts of
prescription fraud. He is accused of writing 18 prescriptions for
morphine and four for the pain killer Demerol to six patients, but
keeping the drugs. That trial has not been scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, he is under investigation in Bay City, Texas, for
the Dec. 19, 1998, death of 87-year-old Laura Ware, said Bay City
Police Capt. Jim Jumonville.
</P>
<P>
   Weitzel cared for Ware at the Legacy Nursing Home in Bay City.
She died at Matagorda General Hospital, where Weitzel also
practiced, but officials there would not comment, citing pending
litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the legal battles ahead for Weitzel, families of his
patients, who had thought their loved ones died peacefully, are
seeking closure.
</P>
<P>
   Merlin Larsen's brother, Harold, said he knew nothing about
Weitzel until the charges were filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's been in trouble every place he's ever worked. We pity him
because he's made such a mess of his life,'' he said. ''We're
hoping that we can put a conclusion to it. Maybe the trial will do
that, maybe it won't. I don't know.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1224 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 34; Dow Up 16  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mixed today as investors wondered
whether some new signs of slower economic growth mean that the
Federal Reserve is nearing the end of its long run of interest-rate
increases.
</P>
<P>
   In midday trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite index was
down 33.56 at 3,425.92, teetering between gains and losses. On
Tuesday, the index rose 254.37 points, or 7.9 percent -- its largest
percentage gain ever and the second-largest point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators, which joined the Nasdaq in Tuesday's
rally, were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 16.44 at
10,543.57 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was down 0.52 at
1,421.93.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said interest rate worries were preventing the market
from building decisively on Tuesday's gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're going to see these periodic rallies, but I don't
think they'll be sustainable because of the nervousness that's
lingering over monetary policy,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks shook off some early weakness after three separate
economic reports offered signs that the economy is no longer
growing at the rapid pace that prompted the Federal Reserve to
raise interest rates six times in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the most significant report was data from the
Purchasing Management Association of Chicago. The group's index of
area business activity fell to 53.9 in May, on a seasonally
adjusted basis, from 56.5 in April. The report is considered a good
gauge of the national purchasing managers' report, due out on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, the Commerce Department reported that sales of new
homes tumbled 5.8 percent in April. That marked the largest decline
since last September.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators declined
by 0.1 percent last month, the Conference Board said today. The
compilation of forward-pointing economic statistics is designed to
forecast the future direction of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The three reports should convince investors that the Fed's
efforts to quell inflation are succeeding, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy is already showing evidence of a slowing rate of
expansion,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, pointing to reports last week
that showed declines in existing home sales and consumer
confidence. ''Inflation reports remain benign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street was already looking ahead to the government's
employment report for the month of May, due out Friday. That report
should indicate whether a continued low jobless rate is forcing
companies to boost wages and benefits to retain workers.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies fell ~ to 57[. The company, the world's
biggest maker of telephone equipment, is acquiring Chromatis
Networks, a privately held optical networking firm, for about $4.5
billion in stock. Lucent said the deal would will help it gain
business in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart rose 1 1/16 to 8 11/16. The company tapped the No. 2
executive at drug chain CVS Corp. as its new leader, replacing
Floyd Hall, who announced in mid-May that he was planning to retire
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 402.21 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.34 to 477.04.
</P>
<P>
   ------
