<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Carly Simon Celebrates New Album  </HEADLINE>
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Carly Simon says she didn't try to write a song
about her struggle with cancer; instead the song, ''Scar,'' led
her.
</P>
<P>
   ''One day in my bathtub I was looking out the window at snow and
I wrote the first verse. I was thinking about my scar and how it is
something that would make a person who is loved more lovable,'' she
says. ''If you love somebody, you just want to kiss and protect
their scars; you want to protect the things about them that make
them vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon, whose new album, ''The Bedroom Tapes,'' was released May
16 by Arista, says she's now in good health, and has gotten over a
bout with writer's block, recovered from depression, and moved from
New York to Boston to Martha's Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm feeling so much as if music once again has come to my
rescue,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Bedroom Tapes'' is a look at what's been going on in her
life. The bedroom, she hastens to explain, is daughter Sally's old
room in the house on Martha's Vineyard, where Simon now lives full
time and where she did most of the recording.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote most of the songs for the CD while she was undergoing
chemotherapy for breast cancer. ''I think the reason is that when
you have a life-threatening illness, you call upon life itself to
fight it. You get more and more involved in life, whatever that
means to you. For me, it was music,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   After finishing chemotherapy, Simon, 54, went into depression
from the chemicals for about six months. The song ''I Forget'' is
about that experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''I waited for the sun to go down so I could go to bed. It was
that long tunnel where you don't see the light at the end,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   ''People may forget life was ever good and not recognize the
symptoms as being depression. I hope that people, if they listen to
the song and recognize themselves, will get treatment.''
</P>
<P>
   One verse of ''Scar'' is about a friend who phoned and said he
wanted to see her, but who didn't call again after she told him she
was healing from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of people during my illness avoided me,'' Simon says.
''I think they were frightened of their own mortality. They didn't
want to talk to anybody fighting a life-threatening disease.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have a lot of compassion for people who don't know what to
say. Not everybody has strengths in the same area.''
</P>
<P>
   The breast cancer diagnosis came in October 1997, with surgery
that November and chemotherapy from January to June 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Her writer's block arrived earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ''Around 1996, everything was coming out like garbage,'' she
says. ''I'd had slumps before, but nothing nearly as long-term as
that one.''
</P>
<P>
   She decided not to write songs anymore, and in 1997 released
''Film Noir,'' an album of songs from films.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was thinking music had abandoned me,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the end for writer's block came when she heard
''Embraceable You'' on a jukebox. That led to the first song she
wrote for the new album, ''In Honor of You (George).''
</P>
<P>
   ''I was the person who had lost her way in the song. I found it
again by imagining George Gershwin sitting in summer heat, writing
that song, looking for the hook,'' Simon says.
</P>
<P>
   After that, she didn't write for another year and a half, until
early 1998. But she was thinking about writing songs in a free
form. ''A lot don't have choruses,'' she says. ''They go wherever
they want to. They have an overriding sense of something I want to
say.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon had made one album with her sister, Lucy, in 1964, before
her solo career started. Most of her hits came in the 1970s,
including ''That's the Way I've Always Heard it Should Be,''
''Anticipation,'' ''You're So Vain,'' ''Haven't Got Time for the
Pain'' and ''Nobody Does it Better.'' There also was ''Jesse,'' in
1980, and ''Let the River Run,'' in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Simon's fear of appearing on stage seems to be receding, and
this summer she will do some singing in public. She says she
enjoyed a recent concert in New Orleans with her children, Sally
and Ben, both of whom are performing and recording. They were born
when she was married to James Taylor. Since 1987, she has been
married to businessman and poet Jim Hart.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says she doesn't have a favorite song on the new album,
though she enjoys moving to the beat of ''Big Dumb Guy'' and likes
''Actress,'' which was inspired by hearing little girls worrying
about bad camera angles after an audition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I could easily put myself in that place -- a little girl
putting on lipstick, imagining I was going to be a movie star one
day. It became my voice. Sometimes songs start with somebody else's
voice and become my voice,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Simon says she's happy now.
</P>
<P>
   ''All kinds of really positive things are happening. I'm
thinking with the release of this record how much I feel as if I've
been rejuvenated,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   ''My health seems to be fine now,'' she says. ''I'm thriving and
enjoying life more than I ever have and I'm very happy living on
Martha's Vineyard and just feeling great. I get scared every time I
go to the doctor for a checkup, but I did that before I got cancer,
too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
