<BODY>
<HEADLINE> On Stage: Has Bogosian Gone Soft?  </HEADLINE>
By DOUGLAS J. ROWE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Has Eric Bogosian gone soft?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, he says, but it's more like society has hardened.
</P>
<P>
   In his latest one-man show, ''Wake Up and Smell the Coffee,''
off-Broadway's erstwhile angry young man says, ''I can talk the
talk. I can't walk the walk. ... I toe the line ... Show me the
line -- I get in it. That's the kind of rebel I am.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics used the words ''midlife crisis,'' ''mellow,'' even
''sweet-natured'' in characterizing his latest production. One
reviewer noted that the ''targets in his 90-minute show are dated
or unworthy'' of his talents. He takes aim at materialism,
terrorist violence (the 1995 Oklahoma City bombing), self-help
gurus, the glorification of stupidity in movies and the seeming
capriciousness of God.
</P>
<P>
   It's as if the cartoon of the snarling, jagged-toothed dog
attacking a cup of coffee on the Playbill cover should be defanged
-- or replaced by the insipid image of someone shooting fish in a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm only putting out what's going on with me, and I suppose
that I must be, on some level, mellower,'' Bogosian says, sitting
in his TriBeCa office strewn with books ranging from a Strindberg
anthology to a compendium of monologues put together by his wife,
Jo Bonney, posters from his and other plays, and newspaper clips
about recent Yankee championships.
</P>
<P>
   While rehearsing the play, he pointed out to Bonney, who is also
the play's director: ''You know there isn't one wino, bum, junkie,
sleazebag in the whole show.''
</P>
<P>
   His Obie-winning one-man efforts ''Drinking in America,'' ''Sex,
Drugs &AMP; Rock 'n' Roll'' and ''Pounding Nails in the Floor With My
Forehead,'' as well as other solo productions that date back to the
late 1970s, often were populated by such types. The closest in his
new show, which also has an array of angry characters, is a
narcissistic creep undergoing therapy.
</P>
<P>
   ''The biggest difference is that times have changed,'' Bogosian
says. ''I realized 10 years ago, when I was watching this TV show
'In Living Color,' and they were doing a sketch about a wino in
front of a supermarket. And I thought, 'Whoa, I was doing stuff
like this 10 years ago. ...' I think the level of irony and
aggression has become just so absorbed in the culture that me
throwing myself around out there doesn't rub people as wrong as it
used to.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never set out to be shocking. I just set out to make stuff
that I like,'' he says. ''Maybe it's mellower. ...''
</P>
<P>
   Outrageousness is such a standard now, he notes, that last
summer's ''South Park'' movie depicted Saddam Hussein and Satan as
lovers.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not even in the same ballpark as that,'' Bogosian says.
''This is the age of Marilyn Manson and Nine Inch Nails, and I'm
not going to get into a competition with them about who can be the
most outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now perhaps putting me out there as a 27-year-old,
semi-junkie, flipped-out, skinny performer was more interesting
than a 47-year-old father of two. ... I don't know. Fellini said,
'You pull your pants down in front of everybody, and if they laugh
at you, it's your tough luck.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian doesn't think his new show represents a midlife crisis,
as one reviewer suggested, but he concedes he's had one recently.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question in my mind that's what I've been going
through. When basically I said, 'Wow, I guess I'm over some hill,
and now I'm going to go on to the looking-over-the-shoulder part of
my life.' And I said, 'No, I reject that.' ... There are guys out
there who are 80 years old who are rockin' and I'm going to do it
to the end, too,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ''You ask me right now, face to face, am I walking the walk? I
think to a certain degree I do walk the walk. My work is walking
the walk -- doing these shows or whatever I'm trying to test myself
with -- and it's been a hard walk lately.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past four years, he says he's been killing himself over
a play he wrote, ''Griller,'' and he can't seem to get all the
kinks out.
</P>
<P>
   A production of ''Griller'' at the Goodman Theatre in Chicago
received poor reviews. ''Gossip,'' a recent movie in which he plays
a sharp-tongued teacher, was widely panned. And now his latest
off-Broadway show -- his sixth full-length solo and his first in six
years -- is ending after an abbreviated run.
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian sounds daunted but unbowed, though. Far from his
acid-tongued, hypercaffeinated stage persona, he's warm, friendly
and accommodating, joking at one point: ''I have no boundaries,
just resentments.''
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Woburn, Mass., about 12 miles outside Boston, the
son of an accountant.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, he would lock himself in his bedroom and pretend to
be different people. Then when a 10th-grade teacher had the class
perform plays, he took to the stage like a natural.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to study theater at Oberlin College in Ohio. When he
graduated in 1976, he headed to Manhattan, where he was caught up
in the downtown performance art world and the strange mixture of
the city's low and high life. The characters who would later define
his monologues began to take shape.
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian fell in with other underground performers, including
Laurie Anderson and Whoopi Goldberg, and he remembers his early
career frustrations, when people hated his work and gigs got
canceled.
</P>
<P>
   He was performing in various small theaters and clubs in 1982,
when the late Joseph Papp, then director of the New York Public
Theater, was so impressed by his one-man show, ''Men Inside,'' that
he scheduled it.
</P>
<P>
   Then from 1986 to 1994, he enjoyed numerous successes: His
off-Broadway one-man show, ''Drinking in America,'' another series
of urban monologues, won an Obie and was followed by the equally
popular ''Talk Radio,'' which Oliver Stone made into a movie
starring Bogosian. He also had a good run at Lincoln Center for his
play, ''subUrbia,'' which Richard Linklater made into a film in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   But he takes hardest the poor reception for ''Griller.'' It's
been criticized as being structurally flawed and having an
incredible ending. Like ''subUrbia,'' it's another tale of the
American Dream knocked off its rails.
</P>
<P>
   The play is set on the Fourth of July. Gussie, a self-made man,
has turned 50 and four generations of his family gather at a
picnic. All reek of success, and yet failure abounds. One son is a
junkie; the other is a driven, egotistical impotent stockbroker,
whose marriage is failing and whose wife has a fling with his
brother before the picnic ends. Meanwhile, Gussie's mother is dying
of cancer. The play ends with Gussie killing his father's alcoholic
friend, and pretending that it was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Bogosian says the negative reception for his play made him want
''to just wrap myself up in wool and say, 'I don't want to play
anymore. I have all my old toys. I like them. They were really
good. And now what I'll do: I'll get real comfy.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he sees himself as ''bopping along in the tradition of
American humor that includes Mark Twain and Lenny Bruce,'' which,
he says, is a lot better than the ''endless revivals'' on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's so easy to congratulate ourselves putting up these
revivals,'' he says. ''Where's now? Now? I want to know about
now!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
