<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Film Shows Algerian Violence  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Flash back: French refugees hug their last few
possessions as the ship carrying them to safety pulls slowly out to
sea. The scene is Algeria 1962, when the North African nation
lurched violently toward independence from France.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward: Black-veiled Muslim women march for peace as
nightly massacres terrorize the population. The scene is Algeria
1994, when the Islamic insurgency against the military-backed
government reached new heights of violence.
</P>
<P>
   These images evoking the torment of modern Algeria are brought
to the screen by French director Alexandre Arcady, 51, a pied-noir,
or French colonial, who fled with his family in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   A box-office hit since it opened in France last month, ''La-bas,
Mon Pays'' (Over There, My Homeland) is the first foreign film to
be shot on location in Algeria in 16 years. It earned high marks
from the press in Algeria after its world premiere there.
</P>
<P>
   ''The film crews stopped traffic. We prepared sets. This wasn't
like making a documentary or filming for the nightly news,'' said
Arcady, who received permission to film from President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika.
</P>
<P>
   Colonial Algeria and the 1.2 million pieds-noirs who fled for
their lives during the 1962 war of independence, including 120,000
Jews like Arcady, have fueled the director's imagination throughout
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ''Le Coup de Sirocco'' and ''Le Grand Carnaval'' are nostalgic
takes on the comfortable life of the French during 130 years of
colonial rule. The blockbuster ''Le Grand Pardon'' (The Day of
Atonement) portrays North African Jewish and Arab mobs fighting for
turf in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   None of those films was shot in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was incredible to be behind the camera in the streets where
I played as a kid, in the house where I was born, in the cemetery
where my grandmother is buried,'' Arcady said. ''But the Algeria of
my childhood no longer exists.''
</P>
<P>
   Arcady says the film's very existence sends a signal that
Algeria may be ready to renew artistic ties with the West. Before
independence, Algiers boasted 400 movie theaters, mostly
French-owned. Today, there are only 10 in the whole country, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a sign of a new openness and a desire for
change,'' he said at a post-screening debate in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Algeria has been isolated since 1992, when violence erupted
after the army canceled legislative elections that a Muslim
fundamentalist party was poised to win. At least 100,000 people
have died.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Bouteflika, who was elected on a peace platform six
months earlier, invited popular pied-noir singer Enrico Macias,
whose songs evoke passion and longing for Algeria, to perform in
his native Constantine.
</P>
<P>
   In exile since the massacre of family members during the
independence war, the Jewish Macias accepted. The tour was
canceled, however, when Algerian officials bowed to pressure from
18 Muslim clerics who attacked the visit as an attempt to establish
diplomatic ties with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Loosely adapted from a novel by Rene Bonnell, ''La-bas, Mon
Pays'' is the tale of a TV anchorman called back to his native
Algeria to rescue the daughter of his first love, Leila, whose
father was an Arab postal worker and a neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before independence, Christians, Jews and Arabs lived in the
same building, with their front doors always open, sharing each
other's joys and sorrows,'' Arcady said.
</P>
<P>
   That harmony ended when violence broke out and segregation
became the norm.
</P>
<P>
   ''A European walking in an Arab neighborhood or vice versa was
risking his life,'' said Lazare Bouaziz, 66, a retired dentist,
whose family fled the port city of Oran on the eve of the July 1962
massacres.
</P>
<P>
   The film has been popular among pied-noirs who lived through the
period.
</P>
<P>
   ''Arcady could have made a sugar-coated version of our
experience,'' Bouaziz said. ''But instead, he showed the violence
of our exodus -- raw and unembellished.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1227 </TRAILER>
