<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Rick Bayless  </HEADLINE>
By SAMANTHA CRITCHELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rick Bayless can identify the defining moment of
his life. He was 14. While on a family vacation in Mexico, the
Oklahoma native fell deeply in love with the country and the
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Bayless, now 46, planned a career as a Spanish teacher, but had
strong ties to food. His parents owned a barbecue restaurant in
Oklahoma City, and ''we were always hanging out in the kitchen.''
He also taught cooking classes to support himself while he was
getting his doctorate in Latin American anthropological
linguistics.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1980s, Bayless landed the perfect job: He was hired
as a consultant by a small chain of Mexican-American restaurants in
Los Angeles. He spent months at a time exploring different regions
of Mexico -- at someone else's expense.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'd like to do it again, but life's not like that,'' said
Bayless, chef and owner of the Frontera Grill and Topolobampo
restaurants in Chicago, during a recent interview at a Manhattan
hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ''Now I have a 9-year-old daughter and I'd have to get back from
trips like that to see her dance performances,'' he said. ''But
that doesn't mean I don't get those fixes. We go back to Mexico for
shorter trips several times a year.''
</P>
<P>
   His new TV cooking show ''Mexico One Plate at a Time,'' now
airing on public television, is part culinary tutorial, part
travelogue. A companion cookbook with 110 recipes will be released
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most TV cooking tutorials that tape three shows a day in
studio kitchens with high-tech equipment, Bayless uses a single
camera that follows him as he visits marketplaces and restaurants
all over Mexico. It takes three days to film the Mexican segment
for each show, then they shift to Bayless' Chicago home for the
actual cooking.
</P>
<P>
   One benefit of filming in his own home is his wonderful kitchen.
''I have to pinch myself with this kitchen. It's a cook's dream,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   1. This isn't your first TV show, you had one in the late 1970s.
What is different about doing a cooking show now?
</P>
<P>
   Bayless: I did my first show 21 years ago on a nonexistent
budget. I got paid $100 a show, plus I had a $500 research grant.
It was back in the days where the only thing on TV that was cooking
was still only Julia (Child), and she was in her golden era. ... My
series was 26 shows then, and it was all studio and me cooking my
heart out. Nowadays, people are looking for cooking shows to appeal
to a much broader audience.
</P>
<P>
   2. While many of the show's episodes feature tacos, quesadillas
and other foods that sound familiar to U.S. audiences, will viewers
be surprised to see the final products?
</P>
<P>
   Bayless: First of all, tacos have soft shells. American tacos
are no more like Mexican tacos than a ham sandwich. ... When I'm
walking through a Mexican market and I pull out one of those hard
U-shaped shells, it's totally out of place there. Hopefully, I will
teach people to make something infinitely more mouthwatering.
</P>
<P>
   3. What are some other differences between American-Mexican food
and Mexican food?
</P>
<P>
   Bayless: They've started opening Taco Bells in Mexico now and
people consider it American food, which is very ironic. A friend of
mine in a Mexican city said to me, 'You've got to taste this dish,
this American dish. We've got it all over the place in Mexico now.
It's nachos.'
</P>
<P>
   4. Has the Latin craze brought on by pop stars made TV audiences
and restaurant customers more receptive to your food?
</P>
<P>
   Bayless: I think it has, and the growing Latino population in
the United States has made the availability of ingredients much
greater. They are leaking out into ... regular grocery stores.
Twenty years ago, I would talk about jicama and how you'd have to
find yam bean in a Cantonese market. Cilantro we used to call fresh
coriander. It's in any grocery store now.
</P>
<P>
   5. Is there anywhere else in the world that has captured your
attention like Mexico did when you were young?
</P>
<P>
   Bayless: My heart can't be two places at once. But a few years
ago, my wife and I went to Thailand, and Thailand is like the
Mexico of Asia. If I was 14 and I took that family vacation to
Thailand, I bet you that's where I'd be.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1247 </TRAILER>
