<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nashville Sound: Lee Ann Womack  </HEADLINE>
By JIM PATTERSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Lee Ann Womack has struck a chord with
listeners and the country music industry with her Top 10 hit ''I
Hope You Dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The innovative arrangement of a song that urges listeners to
seize the day signals an artistic turn for Nashville, which has
been in a three-year sales slump.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whenever one door closes I hope one more opens/Promise me that
you'll give faith a fighting chance/And when you get the choice to
sit it out or dance/ I hope you dance,'' Womack sings to the
backdrop of a swirling string section arranged by David Campbell,
father of pop star Beck.
</P>
<P>
   The song is one of several this year that have broken out of
country's sound-alike pop mold. Veterans Kathy Mattea, George
Strait and Alan Jackson and newcomers Clay Davidson and Eric
Heatherly have also released progressive singles or albums that set
them apart from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Womack sang backup on Strait and Jackson's ''Murder on Music
Row,'' which criticizes Nashville's lack of support for traditional
country music.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old singer from Jacksonville, Texas, said it's not
important whether one agrees with that point of view, but it helps
stir interest in the genre as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what makes it great -- the passion,'' Womack said.
''When we get to the point where we're afraid we're going to tick
somebody off or something, then we lose some of the really cool
things, I think.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack said her new hit marks a turning point in her career. ''I
think it's going to be the biggest song that I've had yet.
</P>
<P>
   ''As an artist, I'm looking way down the road, and I'm hoping
that I have lots of 'I Hope You Dances' and they get bigger and
bigger,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pop sensibility to the ''I Hope You Dance'' single.
But elsewhere on the same-title CD (MCA Nashville), there is a
touch of Alison Krauss-inspired bluegrass (''The Healing Kind'')
and hard country songs skimmed from the cream of mainstream
Nashville songwriters Rodney Crowell, Bobbie Cryner and Dean
Dillon. The album ends with the old Don Williams hit ''Lord I Hope
This Day Is Good.''
</P>
<P>
   Most encouraging is her inclusion of songs written by Bruce
Robison and Buddy and Julie Miller, stalwarts of Nashville's
so-called alternative country scene.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's such an untapped pool,'' she said. ''People in town are
listening to them, but they're not (recording) them. And I don't
know why.''
</P>
<P>
   Womack, the daughter of a disc jockey, attended Belmont
University in Nashville. She worked as a college intern at MCA
Records years before being signed to a recording contract there.
</P>
<P>
   Her first album ''Lee Ann Womack'' was released in 1997. It was
noted for its hard country sound when country was going through a
pop phase. The ''Some Things I Know'' CD followed in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''I Hope You Dance'' includes three songs produced by Frank
Liddell, her second husband. They are the parents of a 16-month-old
daughter. Womack has a 9-year-old daughter from her marriage to
country singer Jason Sellers.
</P>
<P>
   ''My first job that's primarily on my mind is as a mother,'' she
said. ''When I heard the lyrics to 'I Hope You Dance,' I realized
that those are the things that I want my children to know, that
every mother wants their children to know.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The Web site for MCA Nashville is:
http://www.mca-nashville.com/flash/artists.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1248 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
