<HEADLINE> Clinton Talks Trade in Europe  </HEADLINE>
By ROBERT WIELAARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- President Clinton and European Union
officials failed Wednesday to end bilateral trade disputes but
pledged to work to resolve them through the World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   After a meeting at the Queluz Palace, a sprawling 18th century
guest house outside Lisbon, Clinton told reporters that as he nears
the end of his eight years in the White House, he is leaving
America's overall relations with Europe in fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   He said East European nations were joining the ''trans-Atlantic
mainstream,'' the 15 EU nations were taking charge of their own
security needs within NATO and Russia has completed ''its first
democratic power transfer in its entire history.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing next to Clinton under a hot sun, European Union
Commission President Romano Prodi hailed Clinton's trans-Atlantic
credentials.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi said that while President Kennedy declared himself to be a
Berliner in a June 26, 1963 speech in the German city, Clinton was
''a European. You belong to our family.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, Prodi and Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio
Guterres, whose country now holds the EU presidency, did not report
any progress in their meeting toward resolving disputes over trade
in bananas, beef and genetically modified food.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials said later that the US-EU summit revealed
''lively and frank'' disagreements.
</P>
<P>
   One official, who asked not to be named, said Clinton expressed
his dismay with European subsidies for Airbus planes and ''was
puzzled as to why the Europeans'' were denouncing U.S. efforts to
tone down income tax breaks for U.S. exporters.
</P>
<P>
   The EU accuses the Clinton administration of not doing enough to
get rid of the 15 percent tax break that benefits 6,000 exporters
including such giants as Boeing, General Motors and Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   The WTO views the perk as unfair. And the EU has seized on that
WTO position, especially since the Geneva-based trade organization
has already twice sided with Washington. It has allowed the United
States to impose import penalties of $191 million and $120 million
against the EU for restricting, respectively, imports of bananas
from U.S. multinationals and American beef treated with growth
hormones.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi told reporters that he and Clinton agreed ''all trade
disputes will be settled, case by case, under WTO rules.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides also reaffirmed their commitment to a multilateral
trading system. They said in a joint statement that they believed
''an early launch to an inclusive new round of WTO trade
negotiations would offer a major boost to global economic growth,
employment and sustainable development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
