<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 25; Dow Up 33  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were modestly higher today as investors
wondered whether some new signs of slower economic growth mean that
the Federal Reserve is nearing the end of its long run of
interest-rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   In midafternoon trading on Wall Street, the Nasdaq composite
index was up 24.85 at 3,484.33, having teetered between gains and
losses for much of the session. On Tuesday, the index rose 254.37
points, or 7.9 percent -- its largest percentage gain ever and the
second-largest point gain ever.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators, which joined the Nasdaq in Tuesday's
rally, were mixed. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 32.64 at
10,559.77 and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 11.02 at
1,433.47.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said interest rate worries were preventing the market
from building decisively on Tuesday's gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're going to see these periodic rallies, but I don't
think they'll be sustainable because of the nervousness that's
lingering over monetary policy,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks shook off some early weakness after three separate
economic reports offered signs that the economy is no longer
growing at the rapid pace that prompted the Federal Reserve to
raise interest rates six times in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the most significant report was data from the
Purchasing Management Association of Chicago. The group's index of
area business activity fell to 53.9 in May, on a seasonally
adjusted basis, from 56.5 in April. The report is considered a good
gauge of the national purchasing managers' report, due out on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also today, the Commerce Department reported that sales of new
homes tumbled 5.8 percent in April. That marked the largest decline
since last September.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators declined
by 0.1 percent last month, the Conference Board said today. The
compilation of forward-pointing economic statistics is designed to
forecast the future direction of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The three reports should convince investors that the Fed's
efforts to quell inflation are succeeding, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy is already showing evidence of a slowing rate of
expansion,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, chief market strategist at
A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons in St. Louis, pointing to reports last week
that showed declines in existing home sales and consumer
confidence. ''Inflation reports remain benign.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street was already looking ahead to the government's
employment report for the month of May, due out Friday. That report
should indicate whether a continued low jobless rate is forcing
companies to boost wages and benefits to retain workers.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent Technologies rose $0.688 to $58.688. The company, the
world's biggest maker of telephone equipment, is acquiring
Chromatis Networks, a privately held optical networking firm, for
about $4.5 billion in stock. Lucent said the deal would will help
it gain business in big cities.
</P>
<P>
   Kmart rose $1.25 to $8.875. The company tapped the No. 2
executive at drug chain CVS Corp. as its new leader, replacing
Floyd Hall, who announced in mid-May that he was planning to retire
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 3-to-2 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 611.53 million
shares, ahead of Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 2.65 to 479.35.
</P>
