<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany May Aid U.S. Parents  </HEADLINE>
By TONY CZUCZKA
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- On the eve of President Clinton's visit to Berlin,
the German government is signaling it may help in resolving
international child custody disputes that threaten to strain ties
between the key trans-Atlantic allies.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to raise the increasingly high-profile topic
when he meets German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder in Berlin on
Thursday, the second stop on his European tour.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the cases involve American parents who married
non-Americans, divorced and have since been frustrated in efforts
to gain custody or to see their children. The problem is
particularly acute in Germany, where the decades-long presence of
U.S. troops led to many German-American marriages.
</P>
<P>
   Up to this point, Schroeder's government has taken a hands-off
position in such cases, saying custody fights involving American
parents are exclusively a matter for German courts.
</P>
<P>
   But the government recently has suggested it could change its
position. One approach being considered would set up a group of
lawmakers from both countries to mediate custody fights, government
spokesman Uwe-Karsten Heye said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The issue has complicated German-U.S. ties just when German
policy-makers are fretting that the two partners are drifting apart
after the end of the Cold War, which united the West in opposing
communism.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department has put the number of custody disputes from
mixed German-American marriages at nearly 60. And the U.S. Congress
recently singled out Germany, Sweden and Austria, rebuking them for
allegedly breaching the Hague Convention. The 1980 treaty says
children should be returned to the country that had been their home
in cases where both parents have legal custody.
</P>
<P>
   One impetus for the new focus on the problem is the highly
publicized case of French-born Lady Catherine Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   Meyer has fought to reclaim her sons, ages 12 and 14, since her
German ex-husband refused in 1994 to return them from a visit to
Germany. Meyer, now in Washington as the British ambassador's wife,
has written a book about her experience titled ''They Are My
Children Too.''
</P>
<P>
   In another case, New Yorker Joseph Cooke lost his children --
Danny, 10, and Michelle, almost 9 -- after their German mother
sought treatment for mental illness and turned them over to foster
care seven years ago. A German court ruled in 1995 that the
children had bonded with the foster family and would suffer if they
were returned to their father.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright confronted German Foreign
Minister Joschka Fischer about the Cooke case during Fischer's
visit to Washington in May. Fischer said he was ''deeply
impressed'' by Cooke's plight.
</P>
<P>
   The case of 6-year-old Cuban boy Elian Gonzalez also focused
U.S. attention on the issue. Other such cases are coming to the
fore as hundreds of parents battle for custody across borders and
struggle to reconcile opposing legal systems.
</P>
<P>
   German officials have insisted that they can't influence the
courts, which weigh custody rights against the need to shield
children from traumatic changes. In practice, this means that once
a disputed American-German child has spent more than a year in
Germany -- even if abducted -- courts are reluctant to return the
child to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say a panel of German and French legislators set up
last year to try to broker solutions between rival parents could
now provide a model for countering U.S. criticism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
