<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fujimori Faces Economic Challenges  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- After his tainted re-election victory,
President Alberto Fujimori doesn't just face the threat of
international sanctions and opposition forces eager to topple him.
</P>
<P>
   He must also deal with millions of poor Peruvian supporters who
expect him to deliver what he promised -- jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In the final weeks of a campaign riddled with irregularities and
allegations of vote rigging, Fujimori solidified his support with
promises to create hundreds of thousands of jobs, largely through
government spending.
</P>
<P>
   It's an issue that most Peruvians, out of sheer economic need,
consider more urgent than the sanctity of democratic institutions.
Only one in two people in the labor force has steady work.
</P>
<P>
   But the promises may prove too expensive to fulfill and may have
dangerously inflated expectations among the country's poor.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a time bomb,'' said political scientist Fernando
Rospigliosi, calling Fujimori's pledges ''truly incredible
demagoguery.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Obviously, he won't be able to deliver on these promises nor
satisfy the expectations that were stirred up,'' Rospigliosi said.
</P>
<P>
   The runoff was boycotted by challenger Alejandro Toledo, marred
by violent demonstrations and abandoned by independent monitors,
who said a fair election was impossible without a postponement.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's voting, the U.S. State Department insisted
Fujimori could not ''claim legitimacy'' and called the ballot
''flawed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration was awaiting the outcome of a meeting
Wednesday by the Organization of American States before deciding a
course of action, which could include cuts in direct aid or changes
in U.S. policy toward Peru in international lending organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the international pressure will add to Fujimori's
difficulties in fulfilling the campaign promises,'' said Ricardo
Adrogue, a vice president of economic and marketing analysis for
Salomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   Peru currently receives $177 million in military, anti-narcotics
and humanitarian aid, according to the U.S. Embassy in Lima.
Hundreds of millions of dollars flow into the country from
international lenders, like the Inter-American Development Bank and
World Bank, which fund everything from building highways and
improving health care to financing small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Washington has sent out mixed messages about the severity of
sanctions it might impose. The Clinton administration must walk a
fine line between encouraging fair democratic elections and
avoiding the destabilization of a country that has been its
strongest regional ally in fighting narcotics trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ''Regardless of what the U.S. says or does, it's making Peru
less attractive to investment,'' said Carol Graham, a senior fellow
with the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, Toledo, a former World Bank consultant who
grew up in poverty, had gained ground among Fujimori's traditional
bastion of support, the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks before the second round, Fujimori blitzed the
airwaves with his own promises of ''work for all Peruvians.''
</P>
<P>
   He pledged to kickstart agricultural production with a massive
irrigation project to make the barren Andean sierra bloom. He
promised public works jobs would abound with the construction of
roads and schools, and said the annual flow of foreign tourists
would more than double to 2.5 million by 2005, creating one job for
every two visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But a growing number of financial analysts question where
Fujimori will find the cash to fund his great job push.
</P>
<P>
   International election monitors complained throughout the
campaign that Fujimori was using state-funded public works projects
to pander to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Fujimori denies any pre-election spending binge occurred. But
some economists warn that the burst of spending overshot strict
deficit targets set by the International Monetary Fund. They
predict the government will now have to cut spending in the second
half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has very little room to move in the economic
front,'' said Pablo Secada, an economist with Santander Central
Hispano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
