<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 15:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lucent to pay $4.5 billion for optical networking company with key product </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MURRAY HILL, N.J. (AP) -- The world's largest maker of
communications networking equipment, Lucent Technologies, plans to
buy Herndon, Va.-based Chromatis Networks, an optical networking
firm, in a $4.5 billion stock deal.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent executives are banking the deal, announced Wednesday,
will help them better compete with Cisco Systems Inc. and Nortel
Networks Corp., Lucent's chief rivals in the fast-growing market
for optical networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Chromatis makes a new ''metro optical networking
system'' that can carry data, voice and video traffic together at
the speed of light between large-bandwidth, long-haul networks and
computer users in urban business complexes and high-rise apartments
-- all for about half the current cost.
</P>
<P>
   ''Buying Chromatis allows us to bring the power of optical
networking from the long-haul networks down to a customer's
desktop,'' said Lucent spokesman Bill Price.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Lucent also announced Wednesday that its NetworkCare
Professional Services division and IBM Global Services have formed
a worldwide alliance to enable a new type of service providers
called CyberCarriers to offer businesses, government agencies and
consumers the latest network-based services more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   CyberCarriers, including companies such as AT&AMP;T and Qwest, offer
high-speed networking and data center services, including data
storage and network transport, to customers such as Internet
service providers, Web-hosting companies and e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   In the optical networking field, Lucent's strength has been
creating long-haul networks linking far-flung cities and regions,
according to Price.
</P>
<P>
   Chromatis, which has about 150 employees, is best known for its
Metropolis system, the first in the industry that routes Internet,
data and voice traffic together on metropolitan fiber optic
networks. In addition, the capacity of the system can be increased
by splitting the light beams used to transmit information into many
wavelengths.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe their product is about 12 to 15 months ahead of
everyone else on the market,'' Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Chromatis, which has a research facility near Tel Aviv, Israel,
is testing its Metropolis system with several telephone carriers
and recently signed a five-year contract to deploy the system for
Cogent Communications, which provides Internet service to large
office buildings in 12 major U.S. cities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The combination of Lucent and Chromatis will provide the
industry with next-generation metro optical networks that meet the
cost and capacity requirements for both traditional service
providers as well as the very different requirements of the new
broadband Internet service providers,'' said Bob Barron, chief
executive officer at privately held Chromatis.
</P>
<P>
   Murray Hill-based Lucent will acquire Chromatis for
approximately 78 million shares of Lucent common stock. Tuesday's
closing price of $58.19 per share makes the deal worth about $4.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Several key Chromatis executives could receive an additional 2.5
million shares of Lucent stock, valued at about $145 million,
contingent upon Chromatis meeting certain performance goals, Lucent
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucent expects to complete the purchase by June 30. The company
said the acquisition likely will reduce Lucent's earnings per share
by about 2 cents in the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, and by about a
nickel in fiscal 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The deal excludes a 7 percent stake in Cromatis that Lucent
already owns through its Lucent Venture Partners venture capital
subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   Chromatis, founded in 1998, will become part of Lucent's Optical
Networking Group. Barron and the company's five co-founders will
remain with Lucent, the companies said.
</P>
<P>
   Acquisitions of smaller manufacturers and major factory
expansions have become almost a weekly event in the hot market for
optical network equipment. Demand for network capacity has been
growing exponentially as more businesses try moving into electronic
commerce and more consumers get access to high-speed Web services.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Cisco and Nortel, Lucent's biggest competitors include
JDS Uniphase and Corning.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this spring, Nortel said analysts were forecasting that
the world market for optical networking systems would swell from an
estimated $543 million this year to $15 billion by 2004.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-31-00 1542 </TRAILER>
