<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Recover a Bit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean prices edged back up slightly
Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, recovering from a big
rain-inspired selloff the previous day.
</P>
<P>
   While rain continued to fall in many Midwest growing regions,
market-watchers said the soggy weather had been factored into
prices for now.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean prices consolidated after Tuesday's plunge and also were
supported by a rise in soymeal, attributed to strong export demand
in global markets.
</P>
<P>
   Corn climbed back after dipping to 4{-month lows the previous
day, although forecasts for more rain kept the gains minimal.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures benefited from lower U.S. crop ratings and a small
improvement in overseas export markets.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for July delivery rose { cent to $2.74} a bushel; July
corn rose } cent to $2.25 a bushel; July oats were unchanged at
$1.13 a bushel; July soybeans rose { cent to $5.17{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Beef and pork futures advanced in trading on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .70 cent to 67.77 cents a pound; August
feeder cattle rose .45 cent to 84.77 cents a pound; June lean hogs
rose .48 cent to 68.30 cents a pound; July frozen pork bellies rose
1.85 cents to 87.30 cents a pound.
</P>
