<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India's Nuke Program More Secretive  </HEADLINE>
By RAMOLA TALWAR BADAM
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOMBAY, India (AP) -- India's secret nuclear development program
has just become more secretive, raising concern among some
scientists about safety -- and leading others to suspect that India
is planning to ratchet up weapons production.
</P>
<P>
   A new government order allows India's foremost nuclear body, the
Bhabha Atomic Research Center -- known as BARC -- to effectively
watch over itself. The order eliminates the oversight of the
political appointees on the Atomic Energy Regulatory Board.
</P>
<P>
   The order is dated April 25 and signed by Rajagopalan
Chidambaram, chairman of the Atomic Energy Commission. A copy of
the order was seen by The Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ''Office Memorandum,'' it was meant for the eyes of only
two officials. It says it was issued ''with the approval of the
competent authority'' -- that is, the office of Prime Minister Atal
Bihari Vajpayee.
</P>
<P>
   The order says the ''regulatory and safety functions at BARC ...
will henceforth be exercised through an Internal Safety Committee
structure to be constituted by the director (of) BARC.''
</P>
<P>
   The document had not been publicized in India by Wednesday. But
some regulators and scientists asked to comment spoke out against
it, saying it could lead to danger from unannounced accidents or
leaks and could contribute to weapons buildup in this volatile
region.
</P>
<P>
   Both India and its rival neighbor Pakistan conducted nuclear
weapons tests in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going in a very negative direction,'' said Adinarayana
Gopalakrishnan, chairman of the regulatory board from 1993-96.
''This is as if we've set the clock back 25 years and we're
standing where Russia stood -- totalitarian control and little
concern for the public.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Even during my days we had difficulty monitoring BARC
functions,'' he said. He added that the nuclear center ''had an
unwritten weapons function. This is just making it official.''
</P>
<P>
   A top nuclear scientist who spoke on condition of anonymity said
the new order is intended to maintain secrecy since weapons-related
activities could be scaled up.
</P>
<P>
   Suhas Sukhatme, current chairman of the regulatory board,
confirmed the existence of the order.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm in agreement with the order,'' he said by telephone.
</P>
<P>
   He said that when the board was set up, ''there was a fuzzy line
about what we could and could not oversee. The fuzziness is removed
and clarity has been established.''
</P>
<P>
   Sukhatme said he saw no contradiction in BARC overseeing itself.
''The public need be totally reassured that there is nothing shady
going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts estimate India has enough plutonium to produce 85 to 90
nuclear weapons, and Pakistan has sufficient highly enriched
uranium for 40 nuclear warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Gopalakrishnan, the former regulatory board chairman, said the
need to develop more fissile material may have prompted the new
order.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very definite they plan to go full steam with
weaponization and more laboratories may need to come in ... and
they don't want someone to be snooping around,'' he said from the
southern city of Hyderabad.
</P>
<P>
   Senior scientists within the regulatory board were upset about
the reduction of its authority, saying they fear safety will be the
casualty.
</P>
<P>
   Buddhi Kota Subbarao, a retired naval engineer who worked on
India's nuclear submarine program, said the new order goes against
the concept of nuclear safety.
</P>
<P>
   In Europe and in the United States, regulatory bodies check
civilian nuclear plants as well as monitor the surroundings of
weapons facilities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The person executing cannot be the regulator,'' said Subbarao,
who has argued in court for more autonomy for the
government-appointed regulatory board. ''The concept of a regulator
is to check excesses.''
</P>
<P>
   In a 1995 report Gopalakrishnan submitted to the government, 50
of some 132 safety lapses at nuclear facilities involved BARC.
Gopalakrishnan could not elaborate on the report since he is bound
by India's Official Secrets Act.
</P>
<P>
   Chidambaram, the man who signed the April order and a key
scientist behind India's nuclear weapons tests, did not answer
questions faxed to his office Monday. His office said no answer
could be expected before Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the order, India did not grant inspection rights to
international bodies because it has not signed the Nuclear
Nonproliferation Treaty.
</P>
<P>
   ''Since we do not have inspection rights in India, this is not a
matter for us to get involved in,'' said David Kyd, a spokesman for
the International Atomic Energy Agency in Vienna, Austria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
