<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton May Share Defense Technology  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT
<TEXT>
<P>
   LISBON, Portugal (AP) -- Trying to calm fears of a nuclear arms
race that would leave Europe vulnerable, President Clinton promised
Wednesday to share any new missile defense technology with U.S.
allies, saying ''it would be unethical'' to keep it solely for
America's protection.
</P>
<P>
   Still, European leaders remained uneasy about the proposed
American system. Portuguese Prime Minister Antonio Guterres,
speaking for the European Union, declared, ''We have -- I'll say all
of us -- a main concern'' about the U.S. program.
</P>
<P>
   Addressing a sweep of foreign policy problems at a news
conference on his second day in Europe, Clinton also said there was
''a much greater sense of urgency'' in the Middle East peace
process after Israel's troop withdrawal from southern Lebanon.
''All the balls are up in the air,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Quickening the pace of Mideast diplomacy, Clinton will meet here
Thursday with Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak. He also touched
base by telephone Wednesday with Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   The president spoke in the manicured gardens of the 18th century
Queluz Palace at the conclusion of an inconclusive meeting with
Guterres, who holds the current chairmanship of the 15-nation
European Commission, and EU Commission President Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting failed to resolve trade disputes with Europe over
sales of American beef, bananas and genetically modified food and
tax breaks for U.S. exports.
</P>
<P>
   There was no sense of dismay, though, as all sides sought to
emphasize areas of agreement, such as rebuilding the Balkans and
combatting AIDS, tuberculosis and malaria in poor countries.
Clinton and National Security Adviser Sandy Berger went golfing
after the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Lisbon was the first stop on a week-long journey that will take
Clinton to Berlin and then to Moscow for a weekend summit with
Russian President Vladimir Putin. Clinton also will stop in Ukraine
on the way home Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Despite U.S. efforts to lower expectations for the meeting with
Putin, Clinton said that ''we might make more headway than most
people expect. I'm just not sure.'' But he said he would be
surprised if he and Putin bridged all their differences on missile
defenses and Russia's crackdown in Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said later Clinton's optimism was about an
expected agreement for the United States and Russia to destroy 34
tons of military-grade plutonium on each side. It is enough
plutonium to make tens of thousands of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Russia strenuously opposes U.S. development of an anti-missile
system, arguing it would upset the strategic balance between
Washington and Moscow. Critics of the U.S. system say it will
prompt Russia and China to build up their nuclear arsenals, fuel
tensions with Moscow and separate the United States from Europe's
security.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has promised to announce a decision within months on
whether the United States will proceed with the program, now
estimated to cost $30 billion. His decision will follow a July test
flight of an interceptor rocket after mixed results in earlier
tests.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton hinted that the United States would be willing to share
its missile defense technology with Russia, America's Cold War
adversary.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've done a lot of information sharing already with the
Russians,'' he said. ''We have offered to do more and we would
continue to.'' He said it was inconceivable to develop the
technology for a missile shield against new threats and not make it
available to ''civilized nations'' that are in sync with the United
States on arms control.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it would be unethical not to do so,'' the president
said. ''That's always been my position and I think that is the
position of everyone in this administration.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Clinton refused to embrace the position of
Texas Gov. George Bush, the presumed Republican presidential
nominee, who says the U.S. shield should protect America's allies
overseas.
</P>
<P>
   White House press secretary Joe Lockhart said ''there is a
difference'' between Clinton's and Bush's positions.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials were at a loss to describe what the
United States would do to help protect allies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the ideas are formulated to the point that I can
articulate beyond the president's statement today, where he's
committed to sharing technology,'' Lockhart said. Similarly, Tony
Blinken, the National Security Council's senior director for
European affairs, said, ''I think it's premature to get into it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1614 </TRAILER>
