<HEADLINE> Amnesty: Stop Rebel Diamond Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Amnesty International on Wednesday opened a
campaign aimed at ending the diamond trade from rebel-held areas of
Sierra Leone, asking that all diamonds sold in the world be
identified by the country they came from.
</P>
<P>
   About 60 people protested in front the State Department,
chanting ''No justice, No diamonds'' and carrying signs that read
''Sierra Leone is Dying for Diamonds.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Today, diamond buyers across the United States may be saying
'I love you' with a diamond that has paid for a bloody decade of
rape, amputations and enslavement -- a diamond mined from
rebel-controlled areas of Sierra Leone,'' William F. Schulz,
executive director of the U.S. chapter of the human rights group
said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   He said that governments as well as anyone who buys or sells
diamonds ''should all support a system that separates legitimate
diamonds from those that fund human rights violations.''
</P>
