<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> FCC Adopts Phone Bill Changes  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- All telephone customers are expected to see
savings on their July long-distance bills under a dramatic overhaul
devised by the industry and adopted by the Federal Communications
Commission Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The commission cut by $3.2 billion the ''access fees'' that
local phone companies charge long-distance carriers to connect
calls -- costs that are typically assessed to consumers.
Long-distance companies have pledged to pass on the savings,
meaning their customers should see lower rates.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers that make few or no long-distance calls would see the
most immediate benefits -- with their bills dropping $3 to $4 a
month. Moderate and heavy users stand to gain from falling
long-distance rates or price wars that the new plan may trigger,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's going to affect everyone differently, but overall,
everyone is going to benefit from this plan,'' said FCC Chairman
William Kennard.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers should begin seeing the changes in their July
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have sliced access charges by several billion dollars
over the past few years to better reflect local phone companies'
connection costs -- but Wednesday's reduction is the most dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   The FCC's action implements an industry proposal offered by
long-distance carriers AT&AMP;T and Sprint and major local phone
companies Bell Atlantic, BellSouth, GTE and SBC Communications.
</P>
<P>
   Industry officials said the plan is a major step in moving the
long-distance business toward the trend of flat-rate -- rather than
per-minute -- pricing. That's something that wireless carriers and
Internet providers that offer phone service over their data lines
have already latched onto.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's probably the trend of the future,'' said John Nakahata,
spokesman for the industry coalition. ''This will allow those types
of plans to proliferate.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gene Kimmelman of Consumers Union said the public will
only realize the benefits ''if long-distance companies deliver on
their promise to pass through the savings with rate reductions.''
</P>
<P>
   There is practically no way of measuring whether this is
happening or not, he warned.
</P>
<P>
   Kimmelman did note that the plan offers benefits for those who
make few or no long-distance calls -- long a source of concern for
consumer advocates.
</P>
<P>
   As part of Wednesday's action, AT&AMP;T pledged to eliminate a $3
monthly charge for residential customers on AT&AMP;T's most basic
calling plan, since some consumers make calls totaling less than
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Under AT&AMP;T's basic rate schedule, a consumer that makes 10
minutes of calls a month would save $2.52 a month and more than $30
a year. A person who makes no calls would save $4.71 and more than
$56 a year, the commission said. More than 41 percent of
long-distance users make 10 minutes or less in calls each month.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also folds together and reduces two flat-rate charges
now on monthly bills. One, the subscriber line charge, covers the
cost of the phone line from the local phone company into the home
and is capped at $3.50 a month. A second pays for long-distance
companies' use of the local phone network. It now averages about
$1.50 per month.
</P>
<P>
   These two costs will be consolidated and reduced to $4.35. It
would rise to $5 next July. The commission would then study the
cost to see whether it should be raised further.
</P>
<P>
   A portion of the access fees that long-distance companies
currently pay local phone companies goes toward keeping phone
service affordable for low-income people and those in high-cost
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of contributing to this $650 million fund indirectly,
consumers would see the monthly charge for universal service
assessed by their long-distance carrier spelled out as a separate
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers will also see a separate fee from their local phone
company, averaging about 36 cents, also used to keep phone service
affordable.
</P>
<P>
   These moves fit into the goal outlined by a 1996
telecommunications law of making subsidies explicit and clear to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Federal Communications Commission site:
http://www.fcc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Industry site: http://www.phonepolicy.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1742 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 17:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer, killer's mother plead for his life in murder trial  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. (AP) -- A killer who ignored his victim's pleas
for mercy now wants a judge to show some.
</P>
<P>
   Derek LeCompte, 20, who stabbed a thrift shop owner to death
during a robbery, asked Superior Court Judge Edward J. Turnbach on
Wednesday to spare him the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm asking you to allow me to live,'' LeCompte said.
</P>
<P>
   The killer's mother, lawyers and former principal also urged
Turnbach to have mercy on LeCompte, calling the troubled
high-school dropout a victim of neglect and abuse who doesn't
deserve to die.
</P>
<P>
   LeCompte faces either the death penalty or life in prison for
the May 4, 1999, killing of Linda Thomas, 42, of Lacey Township.
Thomas, owner of The Garage Depot in Toms River, was stabbed more
than 40 times by LeCompte and then left to die as he gathered up
cash and stereo equipment from the store and packed them into her
car.
</P>
<P>
   The killing was captured on videotape by a store surveillance
camera. LeCompte removed it from the videocassette recorder in the
store and threw it out in an apartment complex Dumpster, along with
his bloodied clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The manager of the apartment found the items and contacted
authorities. LeCompte, who was 19 at the time, surrendered a day
later and admitted to the killing.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, LeCompte's mother took the stand, describing her
son as a smart boy who played trombone and belonged to a Young
Astronauts club. Under questioning by defense attorney Robert
Konzelmann, she said the boy witnessed alcoholism and domestic
violence as she took one lover after another into their
trailer-park home.
</P>
<P>
   At 15{, he moved out, first taking up residence in a motel
frequented by crack users and later living out of a car that didn't
run. The two saw each other only once between then and his arrest
for the murder, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Please don't take him away,'' Denise LeCompte told Turnbach,
tears streaming down her cheeks. ''Don't give him the death
penalty. I don't want him to die. My children are all I have
left.''
</P>
<P>
   LeCompte took the stand to read a statement but was not
questioned by his lawyer or the prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Thomas, 37, the victim's husband, left the courtroom
beforehand because he didn't want to hear LeCompte, who apologized
for killing Thomas and said he would turn back time if he could.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Thomas returned moments later to address the court,
standing before Turnbach as Executive Assistant Ocean County
Prosecutor John J. Mercun stood next to him, holding a framed color
photograph of a smiling Linda Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   He told the judge the murder of ''my angel, Linda'' broke his
heart and irrevocably damaged the couple's daughters, Melanie, 17,
and Heather, 12.
</P>
<P>
   ''People say it's better to have lived and loved then not to
have loved at all? They don't know Linda,'' said Douglas Thomas,
who closed the thrift shop after the killing because he couldn't
stand the memory.
</P>
<P>
   Mercun urged Turnbach to condemn LeCompte. He called the killing
premeditated and vicious, citing testimony that LeCompte wore an
extra set of clothing to the store because he knew he would be
bloodied by the time he left.
</P>
<P>
   He killed Thomas so she couldn't testify against him and he even
tried to do away with the ''silent witness'' -- the videotape --
before leaving the store, Mercun said.
</P>
<P>
   ''As she begged and pleaded for her life, he stood over her,
looking into her eyes, with a knife poised over her,'' Mercun said,
his voice rising. ''He rendered his decision 42 times. 'No witness,
no witness, no witness,''' Mercun said, simultaneously thrusting
his hand downward in a stabbing motion, mimicking LeCompte's
killing blows.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he's worthy of death, your honor,'' he told Turnbach.
</P>
<P>
   Turnbach, who must decide whether the aggravating factors
outweigh the mitigating ones, said he would pronounce his sentence
at 9:30 a.m. Thursday. If he spares LeCompte, the killer would get
63 years and nine months in prison and have to serve 85 percent of
it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-31-00 1756 </TRAILER>
