<HEADLINE> Official: No Jerusalem Deal Soon  </HEADLINE>
By SARI BASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A Palestinian official said Wednesday that
Israel has offered to withdraw from more than 90 percent of the
West Bank as part of a peace treaty, but an Israeli official said
that deal would not resolve the status of contested Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The two spoke on the eve of a summit between Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak and President Clinton designed to push forward
negotiations over the treaty. The meeting Thursday is in Lisbon,
Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   A Palestinian official, speaking on condition of anonymity,
confirmed earlier comments by Israeli Interior Minister Natan
Sharansky that Israel has offered to return more than 90 percent of
the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The official said the Palestinians rejected the proposal because
it fell short of demands that Israel give up the entire West Bank
and Gaza Strip, areas captured in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   A close Barak aide, meanwhile, said that the peace treaty being
drafted by Israel and the Palestinians would not resolve the status
of Jerusalem, claimed by both sides as their capital. Jerusalem
Affairs Minister Haim Ramon said it would take a few years to
resolve the thorny issue, and that in the meantime, traditionally
Arab east Jerusalem would remain under total Israeli sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   He dismissed reports that Israel had agreed to Palestinian
municipal autonomy for Arab neighborhoods in the eastern sector but
said there had been some progress in deciding how much land Israel
would return to the Palestinians for their future state.
</P>
<P>
   Barak was cautious about the prospects for an outline for the
treaty, already months overdue.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will see in the coming months if there is a real desire on
the other side to make an agreement and end the conflict,'' Barak
said at a lookout that was the site of 1948 battles over Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   He rescheduled his meeting with Clinton, originally planned for
Thursday evening in Berlin, to Thursday morning in Lisbon so that
he could return home in time to participate in a celebration
marking Israel's 1967 capture of east Jerusalem. Clinton and Barak
are to discuss prospects for reaching a treaty outline.
</P>
<P>
   If progress is made in the talks, the possibility of a summit
between Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Barak and Clinton has
been raised.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat met U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin Indyk in Gaza for
almost two hours and asked for U.S. help with the talks.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am sorry to say that in the last round of negotiations,
there were many obstacles in all directions,'' Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat aide Nabil Abourdeneh said Arafat would meet negotiators
late Wednesday to decide when informal peace talks, originally
scheduled for Wednesday evening, would resume.
</P>
<P>
   The talks are being moved from Sweden to an undisclosed location
in the Middle East. An Israeli official said they would restart
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting unnamed Palestinian sources, Israel Radio said that in
the last round of talks, Israel offered the Palestinians a deal in
which it would annex 15 percent of the West Bank, including areas
in the Jordan valley, lease 10 percent of the West Bank containing
major Jewish settlements for 99 years, and give the Palestinians 75
percent for a future state. The report said Arafat rejected the
offer.
</P>
</TEXT>
