<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Many Jobless After Shahtoosh Ban  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- A court order banning the manufacture of
a soft wool derived from the endangered Tibetan antelope has left
nearly 20,000 workers jobless in Kashmir, a newspaper report said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The government was planning to revive handicraft, handloom and
silk industries in Kashmir to rehabilitate the jobless workers,
Textile Minister Kashi Ram Rana said Tuesday in Srinagar, the
capital of Jammu-Kashmir state, according to The Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Kashmir have suffered since 1989 because of a
civil war by Islamic militants that has discouraged tourism and
prevented them from selling handicrafts.
</P>
<P>
   Shahtoosh shawls, which cost $2,000-$15,000 apiece, are so fine
that even a large one can be pulled through a wedding ring.
</P>
<P>
   Kashmir was the only place where trading in the soft wool was
permitted, until the court passed the order earlier this month on a
suit filed by the Wildlife Protection Society of India.
</P>
<P>
   Tibetan antelope, called chirus, are protected by Indian law.
But Jammu-Kashmir state was exempt because of the special status
accorded to the state when it acceded to India in 1948.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildlife Protection Society said the Kashmir exemption has
been the biggest hurdle to rescuing the chirus, which have dwindled
from 1 million a half century ago to 75,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists say chirus are slaughtered by the thousands in
the Tibetan plateau in China. Their hides are taken to Kashmir,
where the fiber is woven into shawls and scarves by master weavers.
The products eventually make their way to clandestine world
markets.
</P>
<P>
   India is a signatory to the United Nations Convention on
International Trade in Endangered Species, which prohibits the
shahtoosh trade.
</P>
<P>
   The Jammu and Kashmir High Court said earlier this month that
the state must implement all international agreements signed by
India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
