<HEADLINE> Mo. Primary Splitting GOP  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID ESPO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Eyeing an open seat in the House, top
Republicans are wading forcefully into a contested primary as the
party picks a candidate to succeed retiring Democratic Rep. Pat
Danner of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Dennis Hastert intends to campaign for Sam Graves, a
state senator and one of five hopefuls in the primary race,
according to GOP sources who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   That will come as a disappointment to Teresa Loar, a member of
the Kansas City Council and another of the hopefuls. ''I haven't
heard from them, (party leaders) but I've heard from a number of
sources that they prefer a white conservative male to a moderate
female,'' Ms. Loar said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   She said she had tried to reach Rep. Tom Davis of Virginia, head
of the GOP campaign committee, by phone, ''but nobody seems to be
returning my call.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Wilkinson, a spokesman for the House GOP campaign committee,
said top officials there had spoken with Ms. Loar. He said the
committee plans no formal endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Danner, serving her fourth term, announced unexpectedly last
week she would retire. The 66-year-old lawmaker had disclosed
earlier this year she was undergoing treatment for breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Because her withdrawal occurred after the filing period had
closed for candidates, state officials reopened the race to
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Among those jumping in was the congresswoman's son, former state
Sen. Steve Danner, one of four Democratic contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Erik Smith, a spokesman for the House Democratic committee, said
party officials will remain neutral in the race to choose a
candidate. But several Democrats, speaking privately, said the
party hierarchy views Danner as the best chance to keep the seat
from falling into GOP hands.
</P>
<P>
   ''A contested primary in this district is clearly going to hurt
any chance they thought they had of winning the seat,'' Smith said
of the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Wilkinson countered, ''It's a district that (GOP presidential
contender George W.) Bush will carry that we should win.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are defending a narrow House majority in the fall
elections, and Danner is only the eighth Democrat to retire,
compared with 23 GOP lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain is back on the air in New Hampshire, where his
presidential bid soared, this time using his political clout to
campaign for other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   In an ad for Rep. Charles Bass, R-N.H., McCain notes the many
months he spent campaigning for president in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''I made a lot of friends here in New Hampshire, people who are
independent and not afraid to stand up for the things they believe
in -- like Charlie Bass,'' McCain says. ''Charlie's done a good job
in Congress, and most important to me, he's not afraid of straight
talk.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, McCain also taped a spot for Rep. Tom Campbell,
R-Calif., running for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm enjoying it,'' said the Arizona senator, who taped many
ads of his own during his failed presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   A McCain ad for Sen. Spencer Abraham, R-Mich., who is fighting
one of the tightest Senate races in the nation, is on the air now.
McCain also has taped a spot for Republican Jim Cunneen, who is
running for Campbell's spot in the House.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Sending a fund-raising solicitation to a not-so-receptive group
is an occupational hazard in the days of multimillion dollar
campaigns. And Rick Lazio's newly hatched Senate campaign in New
York has quickly fallen prey.
</P>
<P>
   ''The exciting Kick-Off Reception'' in New York City is set for
June 27, according to a memo. ''There are four levels of
commitment,'' from members, who agree to raise $10,000, to general
chairs who commit to raise $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the recipients of the memo included Emily's
List, an organization devoted to electing Democratic women
candidates who favor abortion rights, and which is supporting first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton against Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Malcolm, the organization's president, responded tartly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, I cannot attend, would not like my name listed
on the invitation, and will not raise any money for Mr. Lazio,''
she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   She went on to say that Lazio ''is not pro-choice ... is not a
Democrat ... is not a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Associated Press Writer Laura Meckler
contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
