<HEADLINE> Argentine Workers Protest Program  </HEADLINE>
By KEVIN GRAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- Thousands of workers rallied
Wednesday against the International Monetary Fund and a government
plan of taxes and spending cuts intended to re-ignite Argentina's
stagnant economy.
</P>
<P>
   The protest led by two union groups was timed for the arrival of
an IMF delegation consulting on the government's economic recovery
program.
</P>
<P>
   Many government workers joined in the rally, abandoning their
desks at midday to join the thousands of protesters hoisting union
banners and waving Argentine flags, as they marched through
downtown Buenos Aires to a leafy plaza fronting Argentina's
Government House.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are capable of defeating the financial dictatorship,''
shouted labor leader Hugo Moyano, referring to international
financial organizations. Labor leaders took turns addressing the
crowd, condemning the economics of a ''savage capitalism'' before
Moyano announced plans for national strike June 9.
</P>
<P>
   The government plan ''has produced a heavy tax burden that has
only brought misery,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando De la Rua on Monday announced a new round of
spending cuts to resuscitate South America's second-largest
economy. He called for sharp cuts in state salaries and state
pensions to trim the $7.1 billion deficit by $2.5 billion this
year, as required by law.
</P>
<P>
   ''These measures aren't against anyone, but instead are for the
better for everyone,'' De la Rua told reporters Wednesday. ''They
are to help create jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Argentina's national joblessness rate has been hovering at 14
percent, and the rate is even higher in the country's cash-strapped
interior.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Teresa Basilio and a fellow group of university professors
joined the march, complaining the cuts would compromise public
education.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government has take several steps but there has been no
economic reactivation,'' she said. ''To the contrary, we are still
stuck. All these economic adjustments are being made on the backs
of the worker.''
</P>
<P>
   Adherence to the deficit-reduction program is in part to help
Argentina maintain access to standby funds from the IMF, if
necessary. Shortly after taking office in December, De la Rua
pushed through an unpopular tax hike and labor reform which helped
Argentina secure a $7.4 billion standby loan.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual move, members of Argentina's Roman Catholic Church
have offered support for the march, as have at least a dozen
congressmen from De La Rua's Alliance party.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
