<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Restricts Media Photographs  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- News photographers in France will have to change
their ways next year under a new law that limits who can be
photographed and how.
</P>
<P>
   France's leading picture magazine, Paris Match, denounced the
law as the toughest in Europe, and said in its Thursday edition
that it was prepared to defy the law and go to court.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, passed Tuesday by the Senate and set to take effect
Jan. 1, is aimed at reinforcing the right to be presumed innocent.
</P>
<P>
   For years, there have been complaints in France that the news
media runs roughshod over judicial procedure regarding the
presumption of innocence. Such complaints gained momentum following
a series of bombings in France in the 1990s and the 1997 death of
Princess Diana.
</P>
<P>
   The law prohibits photographers from taking pictures of suspects
in handcuffs or of victims of crime whose dignity could be
compromised by a visual image.
</P>
<P>
   Publications that print photographs deemed in violation of the
law could face a court-imposed fine of up to $14,000.
</P>
<P>
   French magazines, newspapers and photographers contend that the
law is a form of censorship that limits press freedom and takes
away the constitutionally guaranteed ''right to inform.''
</P>
<P>
   ''France will become the only country in the European Union
where the publication of certain photos will be prohibited under
penalty of heavy fines,'' Paris Match's executive editor, Alain
Genestar, wrote in an editorial published in its latest issue,
dated June 8.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine, whose stock and trade is photographs, called the
law ''outdated and discriminatory'' and said it planned to ignore
it.
</P>
<P>
   If penalized, Genestar said, Paris Match would take its case
before the European Court of Human Rights.
</P>
<P>
   French photographers decry the law as restrictive but say they
are unlikely to soon change their on-the-job behavior because the
final decision to print a picture rests with publications, not the
photographers.
</P>
<P>
   The bill is part of French Justice Minister Elisabeth Guigou's
sweeping reform of the criminal justice system to protect the
rights of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   The law also allows lawyers to be present during questioning of
suspects and gives a special judge the power to terminate or
prolong temporary custody.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1826 </TRAILER>
