<DOCNO> APW20000531.0155 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Villagers Concerned About Division  </HEADLINE>
By MARK LAVIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   GHAJAR, Israel-Lebanon Border (AP) -- For years, the residents of
Ghajar have felt like a soccer ball being kicked around by Syria,
Israel and Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   After last week's Israeli troop withdrawal from Lebanon, the
fate of the Muslim village of 1,800, sitting in a triangle of murky
frontiers, has become even more uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   Ghajar could either remain under Israeli rule, become part of
Lebanon, or be cut in half, depending on the findings of U.N.
cartographers who are remapping the Israeli-Lebanese border.
</P>
<P>
   Most Ghajar residents, who are Alawites like Syrian President
Hafez Assad, said they want to remain in Israel because of the
relative freedom and prosperity they have enjoyed since Israel
captured the village from Syria 33 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Dividing Ghajar is definitely not an option, said villager
Mohammed Issa, 35.
</P>
<P>
   ''What would they do? Draw a line so the children are over here
and the parents are over there?'' Issa said in fluent Hebrew as he
stood outside the three-story white concrete house where he lives
with his wife and six children.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Marwan Ali said experts have not yet reached a
conclusion about Ghajar.
</P>
<P>
   The village sits at the foot of Mount Dov, which Israel captured
from Syria in the 1967 Mideast war.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli soldiers at first marched into the village, but then
withdrew, leaving Ghajar residents cut off on all sides. With
Syrian passports, they could not easily enter Lebanon, while the
Israelis blocked to road to Syria.
</P>
<P>
   So the people of Ghajar asked the Israelis to take over the rest
of their village, allowing them to harvest their fields which
Israel had occupied. In time, villagers took jobs in Israeli towns.
Unlike other villagers under occupation, they accepted Israeli
citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Life with Israel has been good to Ghajar. It has white-painted
houses with blue or green trim, paved streets, a brick-lined
promenade and a green, manicured soccer field that would do a team
in Tel Aviv proud.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're the only Alawite village in Israel,'' said Mussa Vanos,
32, serving food in his little restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   However, the one thing the experts agree on is that Ghajar is
not in Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Amnon Kartin, a geographer at Tel Aviv University, said that
based on colonial maps of the frontier between French-held Lebanon
and French-held Syria, Ghajar was part of Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, Lebanon handed the village to Syria to allow its
residents to reunite with Alawites in Syria, Kartin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lebanese border expert Issam Khalifeh said Ghajar was originally
Lebanese, but that he was not sure about its more recent history.
</P>
<P>
   In another possible clue to a Lebanese past, villagers said they
still owned fields on the Lebanese side of the border that they
could no longer reach to cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   Issa said he preferred to stay under Israeli rule. Raising his
arms in frustration, he said ''it would be awful'' if Ghajar were
attached to south Lebanon, controlled by Hezbollah guerrillas whom
he called ''terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah guerrillas, celebrating Israel's withdrawal last week,
have pledged to continue to fight unless Israel returns all
Lebanese territory, including the disputed area around Mount Dov.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear whether Hezbollah specifically sought control
over Ghajar. The Lebanese government has not claimed the village.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has said it would follow the lead of the United Nations
in determining the final border. U.N. officials are using a 1923
border between French-held Lebanon and British-held Palestine as
their guide.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Cabinet Minister Matan Vilnai met with Ghajar villagers
this week and told them that their Israeli citizenship would have
no bearing on their fate, including a possible division of the
village.
</P>
<P>
   ''It depends on the exact line from 1923,'' Vilnai said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the U.N. Security Council voted Wednesday to keep the
1,053 U.N. military observers on the Golan Heights for six more
months, until Nov. 30.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. Disengagement Force was sent to the heights at the end
of the 1973 Mideast war. The plateau was seized from Syria by
Israel in 1967.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1826 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Counties Donate To Meet Lawmakers  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- An association of county governments,
partially funded by local taxpayer dollars, contributed $20,000
each to the Democratic and Republican parties to help get the ears
of elected officials in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The five-figure ''soft money'' donations allow officials of the
National Association of Counties to attend contributor-only
luncheons, briefings and other events with Congress members.
</P>
<P>
   ''Participating in these two groups gives us access to
leadership on both sides,'' said association spokesman Tom Goodman.
''By being members of these groups, it gives us opportunities to
participate in activities that the DNC and RNC hold. This gives us
additional access that we may not have.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal Election Commission records show the association, which
lobbies on issues important to counties, gave $21,500 in
unregulated soft money to the Republican National Committee last
month. Goodman said the group donated a similar amount to the
Democratic National Committee, which isn't due to report its
contributions until July 15.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said this is the first time the organization has
contributed to the parties.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Makinson, executive director of the nonpartisan Center for
Responsive Politics, said he hadn't heard of local governments or
their associations donating political money in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ''You would hope that the nationwide organization that
represents county governments wouldn't have to resort to paying an
entry fee to meet with politicians in Washington,'' said Makinson,
whose group studies money and campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,800 of the nation's 3,066 counties are members of
the association, and those member counties are home to more than 75
percent of the nation's population.
</P>
<P>
   About one-fifth of the organization's income comes from dues
paid by counties. Other money is earned through rents, royalties
and selling products such as financial services to counties and
their employees.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said the contributions open up another avenue for county
officials to lobby members of Congress and the administration. The
association staff also visits Capitol Hill and county officials
call their own members of Congress on issues.
</P>
<P>
   One issue atop their legislative agenda is the moratorium on
Internet sales taxes. Goodman said businesses that sell on the Web
should pay the same taxes as other businesses. Without those taxes,
states lose revenue, some of which makes its way to county
governments, and local businesses may close their doors because of
the unfair competition, Goodman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a need to find as many ways as possible to meet with
members of Congress,'' Goodman said. ''This gives us one more way
of accomplishing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Makinson said lawmakers should be opening their doors to county
officials without campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ''You've got one level of government paying the ante to talk to
another level of government,'' Makinson said. ''County officials
should be talking to federal officials because they're county
officials, not because they've made a contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   Other givers have also caused controversy. In 1998, the American
Cancer Society made $15,000 contributions to both the Democratic
and Republican governors' associations so representatives of the
charity could attend forums and dinners with the governors, much
like tobacco executives and other special interests do. Spokesman
Roger Salazar said the society no longer makes the donations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
