<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tentative agreement reached to end month long walkout  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WETHERSFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- The American Red Cross and its blood
collection workers in Connecticut reached a tentative three-year
contract agreement Wednesday that would end a monthlong walkout.
</P>
<P>
   The deal came on the 31st day of strike by 200 members of the
American Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees Local
3145. The workers were seeking better pay and less hectic work
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would release details of the deal, saying they
wanted workers to hear the proposal first.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's an improvement over the previous last best offer of the
Red Cross that compelled the strike,'' said Jeffrey Jump, chief
negotiator for the union.
</P>
<P>
   A vote on the deal was scheduled for Saturday. No date has been
set for employees to return to work.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very pleased, looking forward to having our employees
back at their jobs,'' said Lynn Townshend, Red Cross spokeswoman.
''We're relieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Blood collections in Connecticut have dropped to about 100 pints
per day from the usual 600. The Red Cross has been holding only one
blood drive each day, instead of the six to 12 it held before the
strike. The agency hopes to have a full compliment of blood drives
within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Jump predicted the members would ratify the deal. The union's
negotiating committee is unanimously recommending the agreement, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good about it, to say the least,'' Jump said. ''Every
issue has been addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jump thanked state and federal mediators for their help in
reaching an agreement, which came after a full day of negotiations
at the state Department of Labor in Wethersfield. He praised the
striking workers for maintaining solidarity throughout the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''The membership has been remarkable,'' Jump said. ''They have
really stuck this out and persevered.''
</P>
<P>
   Jump attributed the settlement to both sides showing
flexibility.
</P>
<P>
   Although no hospital reported any problems with blood delivery
or service because of the strike, a controversy arose after the
Connecticut AFL-CIO urged the union's 265,000 members to boycott
blood drives until the contract dispute was resolved.
</P>
<P>
   The union had had also asked the American Red Cross ''to cease
the transfer to Connecticut of blood from national inventories or
other centers around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut Hospital Association called that move
irresponsible, and a threat to the blood supply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
