<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Ends Down 59; Dow Down 5  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed mostly lower Wednesday as
investors, viewing signs of slower economic growth with skepticism,
abandoned their belief that the Federal Reserve is close to ending
its string of interest rate increases.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 58.57 to close at 3,400.91,
failing to extend its 254.37-point gain from Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average slipped 4.80 to 10,522.33.
Broader stock indicators, which had joined the Nasdaq in Tuesday's
rally, were also lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 fell 1.85 to
1,420.60.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said interest rate worries prevented the market from
building on Tuesday's gains.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we're going to see these periodic rallies, but I don't
think they'll be sustainable because of the nervousness that's
lingering over monetary policy,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment
strategist at State Street Global Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks slipped despite three separate economic reports that
offered signs that the economy is no longer growing at the rapid
pace that prompted the Federal Reserve to raise interest rates six
times in less than a year.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said the most significant report was data from the
Purchasing Management Association of Chicago. The group's index of
area business activity fell to 53.9 in May, on a seasonally
adjusted basis, from 56.5 in April. The report is considered a good
gauge of the national purchasing managers' report, due out on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the Commerce Department reported that sales of new homes
tumbled 5.8 percent in April. That marked the largest decline since
last September.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators declined
by 0.1 percent last month, the Conference Board said. The
compilation of forward-pointing economic statistics is designed to
forecast the future direction of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   The three reports were encouraging, but not conclusive enough to
convince the Fed that inflation has been tamed, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''(The report) that growth in the factory sector is moderating
is good news for the Fed, but the slowing is nowhere near enough to
keep them from boosting rates further,'' said Mark Vitner,
economist at First Union Securities.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street was also looking ahead to the government's
employment report for the month of May, due out Friday. That report
should indicate whether a continued low jobless rate is forcing
companies to boost wages and benefits to retain workers.
</P>
<P>
   Banks and brokerages were mostly higher. Citigroup rose $1.875
to $62.188 and American Express rose $3.375 to $54.
</P>
<P>
   Investors sold some of the technology stocks that rose
significantly on Tuesday. Qualcomm fell $10 to $66.375.
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard dropped $4.375 to $120.125 after chief executive
Carly Fiorina dismissed speculation that she might announce a
spinoff of Veriphone, a maker of credit-card verification terminals
and e-commerce software.
</P>
<P>
   Riley said that even with Tuesday's rally enticing some buyers
back into the market, many investors are staying away from
technology stocks until the Fed stops raising interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are not immune,'' he said, discounting the theory that
technology companies won't be hurt by rising rates because they
tend to borrow less money than industrial companies. ''They may not
borrow, but their clients do and they will eventually curtail their
technology purchases.''
</P>
<P>
   The tech sector's dizzying spiral downward from its March 10
record has also convinced some investors to broaden their
portfolios into long-neglected sectors outside the technology
world, Riley said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will not see people as committed to one single sector,'' he
said. ''That myopic strategy has led to some disappointing
short-term results.''
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where composite volume totaled 1.14
billion shares, compared with 1.01 billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.52 to 476.18.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.1 percent and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.8 percent. Britain's FT-SE 100 ended nearly unchanged,
slipping 0.3 points.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
