<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Prosecution witness grilled by defense in Peeler trial  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Josephine Lee, who says she was the
lookout when a gunman killed an 8-year-old murder witness and the
boy's mother, was called Wednesday to testify on behalf of the man
accused of arranging the killings.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, the state's star witness against Russell Peeler, testified
earlier in the trial that she overheard Peeler and his brother,
Adrian, plan the murders of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his
mother, Karen Clarke. Lee also said she helped Adrian Peeler get
into the Clarke house and watched as he shot the mother and son on
Jan. 7, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, Peeler's defense attorneys confronted her with
two letters she wrote to her former landlord, Norman Williams, in
which she said she doesn't know anything about the crime and lied
about the Peelers' involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Norman you know that I lied on the Peelers. But I was scared
when the police came to the house to get me so I told them that I
had something to do with the murder. But I do not know anything,''
she wrote in a letter to Williams in May, just after she testified
against Russell Peeler.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who lived across the street from Clarke and her son in a
house owned by Williams, last year pleaded guilty to conspiracy to
commit murder. She agreed to testify against the Peeler brothers in
exchange for a maximum prison sentence of seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Peeler is accused of masterminding the murders to
prevent the boy from testifying against him in the 1998 slaying of
Clarke's boyfriend, Rudolph Snead Jr. His brother, Adrian, is
accused of being the actual triggerman who killed the mother and
son.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning from Peeler's attorneys Wednesday, Lee said
she lied in her letters to Williams because she was hoping to live
in his house when she is released from prison. She later
contradicted herself, saying she did not want to go back to
Williams' house.
</P>
<P>
   She insisted that she was telling the truth when she said she
overheard Russell Peeler ask his brother, Adrian, to kill the
mother and son. She also repeated her original story that she got
Adrian inside the Clarke housing by knocking on the door and
identifying herself as the girl who lived across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ''This right here is a lie,'' she said, holding up one of the
letters she wrote to Williams. ''I'm telling the truth now,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Lee has changed her story.
</P>
<P>
   When Lee first testified as a prosecution witness, Peeler's
attorneys grilled her about a letter she wrote to her own attorney
in Dec. 1999 in which she denied knowing anything about the
killings. At the same time, she sent three separate letters to
Bridgeport police officers in which she said she asked forgiveness
for having a role in the killings.
</P>
<P>
   The defense also called Williams as a witness.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a 75-year-old nicknamed ''Pops,'' said he did not see
Russell Peeler at his house the day before the murder, calling into
question Lee's testimony that she overheard Russell and Adrian
planning the murders as they sat in Williams' house that day.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also said he did not see Adrian Peeler at his house the
day of the murders. Lee testified that Adrian Peeler walked into
Williams' house holding a gun and that she brought him across the
street to Clarke's house with him.
</P>
<P>
   ''Did you see Adrian with Josephine Lee with a gun in his
hand?'' Peeler's attorney, William Koch, asked Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ''No way,'' Williams replied.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination from Bridgeport State's Attorney
Jonathan Benedict, Williams acknowledged that he and others who
stayed in his house had smoked crack cocaine. Lee testified that
Russell Peeler used Williams' kitchen to cook the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Closing arguments in the case are scheduled for Friday. The jury
is expected to begin deliberations Monday after receiving
instruction on the law from the judge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
