<HEADLINE> Big Movers in the Stock Market  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks that moved substantially or traded
heavily Wednesday on the New York Stock Exchange and Nasdaq Stock
Market.
</P>
<P>
NYSE
</P>
<P>
Kmart Corp., up $0.875 at $8.50
</P>
<P>
   The company tapped Charles Conaway, the No. 2 executive at drug
chain CVS Corp., to replace Floyd Hall, who is retiring. Hall was
credited with improving merchandise and store layouts, but the
company's share price lagged behind rivals like Wal-Mart and
Target.
</P>
<P>
Aetna Inc., up $4.063 at $66.75
</P>
<P>
   Shares rose on speculation that the company is in talks to sell
its financial services division to ING Group. Aetna rejected a
prior offer from ING earlier this year. After the close of trading,
Aetna confirmed that it has begun talks with ING.
</P>
<P>
Conseco Inc., up $1.063 at $6.188
</P>
<P>
   Minneapolis businessman Irwin Jacobs is assembling a group of
private and institutional investors interested in bidding for
control of Conseco Inc., Dow Jones Newswires reported.
</P>
<P>
Warnaco Group, down $1.625 at $6.688
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Klein Inc. has sued Warnaco and its chairman, Linda
Wachner, charging trademark violation and breach of fiduciary duty.
Warnaco makes Calvin Klein's core jeans and underwear lines.
</P>
<P>
Geon Co., down $2 at $21.50
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs cut its rating on the stock to ''market
outperform'' from ''recommended for purchase''. Geon makes
polyvinyl chloride resins and compounds.
</P>
<P>
NASDAQ
</P>
<P>
Flextronics International Ltd., up $4.375 at $54.438
Motorola Inc., down $2.875 at $94.25 on the NYSE
</P>
<P>
   Motorola plans to outsource more than $30 billion of
consumer-electronics production over the next five years with
Flextronics and take a small stake in the company. The deal is
believed to be the largest outsourcing agreement between a
name-brand electronics company and a contract manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
Acme Communications Inc., up $2.50 at $12.875
</P>
<P>
   Morgan Stanley Dean Witter raised its rating on the stock to
''strong buy'' from ''outperform.'' Acme operates television
stations, primarily in mid-sized markets around the United States.
</P>
<P>
Anika Therapeutics Inc., down $4.75 at $2.50
</P>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission issued a formal order of
investigation regarding Anika's revenue-recognition policies. Also,
Anika's Orthovisc drug, designed to treat osteoarthritis of the
knee, failed to provide better relief than a saline control in
late-stage clinical trials.
</P>
