<HEADLINE> Lawmakers Fear Russian Uranium  </HEADLINE>
By KATHERINE RIZZO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russia has proposed selling extra
commercial-grade uranium to a U.S. company, but lawmakers want the
Clinton administration to reject the deal, contending it could lead
American uranium plants to close.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers worry that if more ready-to-use uranium is
available from Russia, there will be less need for enriched
American uranium and jobs will be lost.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Enrichment Corp. has plants in Piketon, Ohio, and
Paducah, Ky., the only plants in the country where uranium is
enriched. A plant in Metropolis, Ill., is the sole one that readies
uranium for enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers from the three states have asked the administration to
reject the deal with the Bethesda, Md.-based company. The National
Security Council and State Department would have to agree to any
new arrangement with Russia before it could proceed to further
consideration by the Commerce Department.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a bad idea,'' Rep. Ted Strickland, D-Ohio, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A letter signed by 19 members of the Illinois congressional
delegation said the Illinois plant already is ''on the verge of
shutting down.'' A deal with Russia ''may greatly exacerbate an
already serious situation,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   The company president, in a letter to Congress, insisted there
would be no connection between a plant-closing decision and a deal
with Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The quantity of low-enriched uranium under discussion ''will not
trip a decision to cease enrichment at one of our plants,'' William
Timbers wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The company was part of the federal government before it was
spun off in 1998 in a $1.9 billion stock sale. It provides uranium
fuel for civilian power plants, accounting for about a third of the
worldwide market.
</P>
<P>
   Its profits have declined sharply because of a slump in the
uranium market and increasing costs at the aging enrichment plants.
The company, which is in the process of eliminating 625 of its
2,800 jobs, also says it has lost money on a deal to buy Russia's
uranium stockpile and sell it to utility companies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, Timbers acknowledged the Russians have proposed
selling commercial-grade uranium, and confirmed that it arose
during talks to renegotiate the price of uranium being salvaged
from nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial-grade uranium would not require processing at the
Illinois, Ohio and Kentucky plants, but Timbers said that would not
mean the plants would have to close.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal goes through, the company would release the Russian
uranium on to the market as part of a package deal, sold only ''if
matched with material manufactured in our country by our
employees,'' according to the letter.
</P>
<P>
   ''This matched material will be used to make high-cost U.S.
produced (uranium) more attractive to our customers and help us
beat the aggressive foreign competition,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   To Strickland and Rep. Ed Whitfield, R-Ky., an arrangement to
buy utility-ready uranium would turn the company into a broker that
someday could decide to serve all its customers with foreign
uranium.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nothing would encourage the demise of our domestic industry in
the same way that this would,'' Strickland said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.usec.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 1910 </TRAILER>
