<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio promises high road, blasts Clinton as ''far left''  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATKINS GLEN, N.Y. (AP) -- While pledging aboard his ''Mainstream
Express'' campaign bus to ''take the high road'' against Senate
rival Hillary Rodham Clinton, Rick Lazio launched one of his most
stinging attacks to date against the first lady on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with The Associated Press aboard his customized
campaign cruiser on the way to Watkins Glen in the Finger Lakes,
Lazio said New Yorkers should be asking themselves: ''What have you
done for us for the last eight years? Have you been in our corner,
or are you just a Johnny-come-lately who is aspiring to a position?
Is this about ambition or is this about public service?''
</P>
<P>
   New York Republicans have been complaining for months that
Clinton is a carpetbagger who wants to use the Senate seat as a
stepping stone to a run for president.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio refused to say what he thought the first lady's ambitions
might be, but maintained that he harbored no presidential
aspirations of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this will be the pinnacle of my career,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate interview with CNN, Lazio showed a softer side,
tearing up when he talked about his late father, Anthony Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he'd be very proud of this,'' Lazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The trip marked the first full day of campaigning for the
little-known congressman from Long Island aboard his newly acquired
campaign bus, a coach reminiscent of Sen. John McCain's ''Straight
Talk Express.'' It was also the first day on the road for Lazio
since picking up the Republican Party's Senate nomination at the
state GOP convention in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio began Wednesday in Syracuse and hit the trail already
prepared to do battle, and work at raising his name recognition
with voters.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a struggle between somebody on the far left and
somebody in the center,'' he told reporters before boarding his bus
for a trip to the nearby Byrne Dairy milk plant where he and his
wife were treated to ice cream cones.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he had dubbed the bus the ''Mainstream Express'' for
two reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ''One is to reinforce my record in the house which is a
mainstream record which is, I think, where the vast majority of New
Yorkers are,'' Lazio said. ''The second thing is to reinforce this
is a grassroots campaign and we're going to be out and open and
among the people.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm going to be here answering your questions like I am right
now at every stop,'' he added. ''We're going to be accessible. I
expect to be held accountable ... I think that's what this campaign
should be all about. It shouldn't be about rope lines and checking
credentials and scripted responses.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Lazio's own acceptance speech to the GOP convention
on Tuesday had contained the stage direction to ''smile'' at one
point, Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said: ''Candidates
in glass buses shouldn't throw stones. Once again, Rick Lazio's
rhetoric doesn't match reality.'' He also suggested a better name
for Lazio's bus would be ''the double-talk express.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Lazio's new bus was something of a carpetbagger,
sporting a temporary registration plate from Alabama. Inside was a
makeup artist, on hand to help conceal the split lip he suffered
Monday when he took a tumble during a Memorial Day parade.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfson also said, ''It sounds like Congressman Lazio has taken
the low road out of Buffalo, offering more insults instead of
ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Stopping at the Glenora Wine Cellars, overlooking Seneca Lake
just outside Watkins Glen, Lazio told Yates County Republicans that
he would be a fiscally responsible senator.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want any blank-check philosophy here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later, at a news conference, Lazio was asked to explain
what it was that made Clinton a candidate of the ''far left.'' He
demurred, other than to mention her unsuccessful attempt to
overhaul the nation's health care financing system.
</P>
<P>
   ''People are going to try to get me into this, 'He said, she
said' deal,'' the congressman said. ''I only want to talk about who
I am and what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his not-too-subtle attacks on Clinton, Lazio and
his supporters appeared determined Wednesday to convince New
Yorkers he really was a ''mainstream'' Republican and not the
right-wing, Newt Gingrich-loving conservative the Clinton camp has
been making him out to be.
</P>
<P>
   ''Rick is middle-of-the-road,'' moderate Amo Houghton, a fellow
New York Republican congressman, told a rally in Watkins Glen.
''We're not extremists.''
</P>
<P>
   During a walking tour of Watkins Glen, where sports cars once
raced through the streets, Lazio was greeted warmly and given
encouragement from locals and visitors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're tired of the word 'Clinton,''' Jonathan Ciener, 51, of
Cocoa Beach, Fla., told the congressman. The owner of a company
that manufactures gun accessories had his Ferrari parked across the
street.
</P>
<P>
   ''Kick her ass, Rick,'' the driver of a van shouted out his
window. The congressman, dressed casually in a polo shirt, blue
blazer and khakis, waved.
</P>
<P>
   At a campaign stop in Elmira later Wednesday, Lazio was greeted
by an enthusiastic crowd of about 150.
</P>
<P>
   At a later rally in Binghamton, Lazio again attacked Clinton for
being a non-New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   ''Being a New Yorker is more than moving into a multimillion
dollar house and putting a Yankee hat on,'' Lazio told a sparse but
enthusiastic crowd of no more than 250 people.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in the audience was a Lazio supporter. Mary
Franzonello over nearby Endwell said she was a conservative
Republican and that Lazio just wasn't conservative enough for her.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't want Hillary, but what's Lazio offering us as a real
alternative,'' she said while carrying a six foot high photograph
of Hillary Clinton with words coming out of her mouth that said
''Lazio and I share views on abortion, gun control and the
environment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
