<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Census: 92 Percent of Work Done  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 110 million households counted, and
another 10 million to go.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau announced Wednesday it has reached 92 percent
of the roughly 120 million U.S. households, either by mail or
through a visit from a census-taker at the front door.
</P>
<P>
   But Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt acknowledged that
those homes still uncounted will be the toughest task yet for his
census-takers. He said he hoped an encouraging e-mail sent
Wednesday from President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore to all
Census Bureau employees will help.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am extremely gratified that they have sent this message to
all our staff, recognizing the dedication and work that has brought
us to this point,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, the Census Bureau started out with a pool of
about 440,000 part-time enumerators across the country charged with
finding the 42 million households that did not mail back a Census
2000 form.
</P>
<P>
   Those who remain uncounted include hard-to-reach inner-city
residents, anti-government people, and those concerned their
answers will not remain confidential, Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will have to redouble our efforts to reach the remaining 8
percent of households, so that we can deliver to the country the
accurate and complete census it needs for the coming decade,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
