<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Federal panel approves NU, ConEd merger  </HEADLINE>
By CAREN BENJAMIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Federal Energy Regulatory Commission on
Wednesday gave its blessing to the merger of Northeast Utilities
and Consolidated Edison Inc. of New York, but negotiations toward
state approval of the deal stalled in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The $7.5 billion deal would create the country's largest
electric and gas distribution company, with more than 6.4 million
customers in New York and New England.
</P>
<P>
   The federal panel approved the proposed merger without comment
after the utilities allayed concerns about the effect it would have
on competition.
</P>
<P>
   As an example, the companies pointed out they have already spun
off most of their power-generation assets in order to comply with
electric deregulation laws.
</P>
<P>
   NU sold its fossil fuel plants in Connecticut and Massachusetts
well above book value and has put its Millstone nuclear power
plants up for auction.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders from both companies have already approved the
merger.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have also made assurances that customers will not
pay more for electricity as a result of the merger, according to
the regulatory commission's order approving the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are particularly pleased with the speed in which FERC made
the approval as well as the findings in which FERC clearly stated
that the merger with ConEd will not affect competition or energy
pricing,'' said NU spokesman Terrence McIntosh.
</P>
<P>
   The merger still needs approval from regulators in Connecticut,
New York and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Hearings in Connecticut had begun but were cut short in favor of
negotiations after citizens groups complained the state was getting
nothing from the deal.
</P>
<P>
   For the past month Connecticut's Department of Public Utility
Control has been negotiating with the utilities over rate cuts, job
protections, corporate donations, land preservation and other
benefits for customers and the state.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday was the utilities' deadline to file a settlement, ask
for regulatory proceedings to resume or ask to continue talks. No
agreement was reached and NU will ask that the merger hearings
continue, McIntosh said.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut Attorney General Richard Blumenthal said the state
will continue to push for a better deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''When hearings resume at the DPUC, we will continue to oppose
the merger until Connecticut receives substantial benefits and
savings, and Connecticut's economy and work force are protected,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The hearings should start up again in two to three weeks,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission and the U.S. Nuclear
Regulatory Commission must also approve the deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-31-00 2029 </TRAILER>
