<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Coroner Probing 9 Possible E. coli Deaths
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Ontario's chief coroner was investigating nine
deaths Wednesday in connection with the province's killer E. coli
outbreak as Premier Mike Harris finally bowed to pressure and
called a full-scale public inquiry into the tainted water tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Chief coroner James Young stressed that not all the deaths are
necessarily related to the water poisoning in rural Walkerton,
Ontario, but at least seven people are thought to have died from E.
coli infections over recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Two others -- a 92-year-old woman who died May 15 and a
69-year-old man who died May 19 -- have been added to the list of
deaths possibly linked to the outbreak.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry will be wide-ranging and will delve into how the
town's water was tested, how the contamination occurred and whether
government actions or policy played a part.
</P>
<P>
   That could include calling Harris or some of his cabinet
ministers to testify.
</P>
<P>
   ---
British Columbia Treaty Future in Jeopardy
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The future of a treaty
process covering almost all of British Columbia is in jeopardy
after the band furthest along in negotiations pulled out Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Sechelt band, which has always enjoyed a greater degree of
informal self-government than most in the province, has said it
will turn its back on the treaty process and instead ask a court to
hear its land claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government wants to cram their final statements down our
throats,'' Chief Garry Feschuk said at a ceremony Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Feschuck said even when he signed the agreement in principle
last year, he knew there were a lot of issues to be addressed, but
he said he thought that could be done before a final treaty was
signed.
</P>
<P>
   He said it will take three months for the court process to kick
in. In that time, the band is willing to listen to any further
offers from the federal and provincial governments.
</P>
</TEXT>
