<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile's Leader Offers Land  </HEADLINE>
By EDUARDO GALLARDO
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) -- President Ricardo Lagos offered land and
money to restive Mapuche Indians on Wednesday, but warned that
violent opposition to timber and electric companies in southern
Chile will not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ''We all must act within a state of law,'' Lagos said in
announcing the creation of a ''truth'' commission, his first major
initiative to resolve the demands of Chile's poor Indian
minorities.
</P>
<P>
   The Mapuche Indians have long been demanding what they consider
their ancestral lands, and some have engaged in violent clashes
against timber projects and a hydroelectric dam being built 350
miles south of Santiago.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos vowed on the campaign trail last year to quickly tackle
the Indians' problems and solve their land disputes. His latest
move came a year after his predecessor Eduardo Frei signed a
landmark anti-discrimination pact with the indigenous communities.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from the various tribes attended Wednesday's
ceremony at the presidential palace for the creation of the
so-called Commission for Historic Truth and a New Deal.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, grouping officials, scholars, businessmen and
Indian representatives, is supposed to study the past and present
situation of Chile's 1.2 million native Indians, mostly Mapuches
living in the south. It is to propose measures to solve their main
problems -- poverty, discrimination, joblessness, lack of land and
poor education.
</P>
<P>
   Lagos used the occasion to announce that the Mapuche will be
given some 370,500 acres of government-owned land, one third of it
before the end of 2001.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, 10,000 Mapuche families will be granted $192 each
to buy seeds and other agricultural products, Lagos said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lagos insisted violent actions would not be tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot permit small groups to stymie Chile's development,''
Lagos said, a reference to the Mapuche opposition to the
multi-million dollar Ralco dam project. ''But at the same time we
will not impose on these groups conditions that are unacceptable to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   --------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Website for government agency on Indian affairs, in Spanish,
http://www.conadi.cl
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
