<HEADLINE> Cardinal O'Connors Will Filed  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Cardinal John O'Connor left nearly all of his
possessions to church groups, according to his will filed
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor left most of his religious items to the New York
Archdiocese, which he led for 16 years until his death May 3. Those
items include his Episcopal ring and all religious vessels,
vestments and objects.
</P>
<P>
   The exception was the chalice that he was given when he was
ordained as a priest in 1945. He left that to the Sisters of Life,
the order of nuns that he founded 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Agnes Mary Donovan, head of the order, called the bequest
to the 42-member group ''a blessing from our spiritual father and
founder.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor died at age 80 after a battle with cancer.
</P>
