<HEADLINE> NY Teen's Death Ruled Homicide  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) --Soon after Josh Slaughter was born, police say he
was shaken so violently his brain was injured, causing the onset of
cerebral palsy. Police arrested his mother and she later pleaded
guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 14 years later, the medical examiner's office has ruled his
death in April a homicide, stemming from the shaking when he was
about 3 months old.
</P>
<P>
   The district attorney is reviewing the case and has not decided
whether charges will be brought against Mitzi Slaughter, 38, in her
son's death.
</P>
<P>
   She was questioned by police on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Slaughter had pleaded guilty in 1988 to second-degree assault
for shaking her son and served a six-month jail sentence and five
years probation.
</P>
<P>
   After her arrest, Josh was placed in the care of the city's
children's welfare agency. He lived in foster homes until 1997,
when he was transferred to a facility run by United Cerebral Palsy
of New York State. Officials at that facility did not return calls
for comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to the medical examiner, Josh's death April 12 was
caused by bronchial pneumonia with septicemia, meaning he had a
blood infection. He also had complications stemming from a
neurological disorder that resulted from his being shaken as an
infant, said Ellen Borakove, a spokeswoman for the medical
examiner's office.
</P>
</TEXT>
