<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Son of President Coolidge Dies  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER GRAFF
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- John Coolidge, the oldest living
offspring of an American president, died Wednesday at 93.
</P>
<P>
   The son of President Calvin Coolidge died at the
Dartmouth-Hitchcock Medical Center in Lebanon, N.H., after being
hospitalized for respiratory problems, said a spokesman for the
Calvin Coolidge Memorial Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   ''John Coolidge was very much like his father,'' said historian
Howard Coffin. ''He was a man of few words, but what came out were
well chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   John Coolidge was at military camp in the summer of 1923 when
his father became president upon the death of Warren Harding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was taking summer military training at Fort Devens,
Massachusetts, and didn't know anything about it,'' John Coolidge
once said of his father's swearing in. ''In fact, the next morning,
I was standing in line for breakfast when a captain came by and
asked me if I'd seen the morning papers.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I told him no, he said, 'Your father is the president of
the United States.' Naturally, I was surprised, but nothing
changed. I guess a lot of people expected me to rush off to
Washington, but I stayed and finished training.
</P>
<P>
   ''Father wouldn't have it any other way.''
</P>
<P>
   John Coolidge was born Sept. 7, 1906, in Northampton, Mass. He
spent most of his adult life in Connecticut where he was a railroad
executive and operated a business in Hartford. He also worked to
preserve the buildings that make up the President Calvin Coolidge
State Historic Site.
</P>
<P>
   ''He bought property time and again when the state didn't have
money, and it became part of the site,'' said John Dumville of the
state division of historic preservation. ''He gave generously of
things that belonged to his mother and father.''
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge is survived by a daughter, three grandchildren and two
great-grandsons. His wife, Florence, died in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 2144 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000531.0184 </DOCNO>
