   Nelson said Hindelang is expected to be released from the
hospital Saturday. Nelson also said doctors told Hindelang he won't
be able to travel for two weeks after he is released, making it
doubtful he would go to Omaha if Penn State advances.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our No. 1 concern, however, is that Joe receives the proper
medical attention and experiences a speedy and complete recovery,''
athletic director Tim Curley said.
</P>
<P>
   Hindelang started coaching the Nittany Lions in 1991 after
coaching at Lafayette and the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy. He
played baseball and basketball at Temple University.
