<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Wednesday, May 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
UN Reports on Women's Progress
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In an assessment of women's progress toward equality,
the United Nations reported today that more girls are attending school -- but
that all females still confront ''a global epidemic'' of violence. The mixed
snapshot for women five years after a major international women's conference in
Beijing shows they comprise an increasing share of the world's labor force but
are making no headway in cracking the top echelons of business and government.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gore: Don't Ban Cigarettes
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MACON, Ga. (AP) -- Vice President Al Gore, confronted by a handful of angry
tobacco workers, said today he does not want to make cigarettes illegal and
would do what he could to protect tobacco-industry jobs -- as long as it doesn't
undercut efforts to keep kids from smoking. ''I am happy to do anything I can to
help you preserve your livelihood, but I am not going to say or do anything that
in any way undermines or weakens the toughest possible measures to prevent
children from ever getting into the habit of smoking,'' Gore said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Official: No Jerusalem Deal Soon
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A Palestinian official said Wednesday that Israel has
offered to withdraw from more than 90 percent of the West Bank as part of a
peace treaty, but an Israeli official said that deal would not resolve the
status of contested Jerusalem. The two spoke on the eve of a summit between
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and President Clinton designed to push forward
negotiations over the treaty. The meeting Thursday is in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain Skips Bush Visit To Arizona
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- George W. Bush picked up political cash and support in
Arizona today, while his former presidential rival, Sen. John McCain, stayed
away from a fund-raiser involving the ''soft money'' donations he opposes. ''He
has stated all along that he will do everything he can for the Republican Party
and for Governor Bush, but he will not help to raise soft money,'' said McCain
spokesman Todd Harris. The Arizona senator, who endorsed Bush on May 9, was
campaigning for congressional candidates in California instead.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fla. School Suspect Told Of Plans
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LAKE WORTH, Fla. (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy charged with killing a teacher
after being sent home from school for throwing water balloons told a classmate
he planned to return and shoot the counselor who suspended him, police said
today. ''Just watch, I'll be all over the news,'' Nathaniel Brazill told the
girl, according to Police Chief William Smith. The girl, also 13, didn't take
him seriously, just as other students had not when he talked about shooting
someone in the days leading up to the Friday's shooting of English teacher Barry
Grunow.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FCC Change Will Lower Phone Bills
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- All telephone customers are expected to see savings
beginning with their July long-distance bills under a dramatic overhaul devised
by the industry and adopted by the Federal Communications Commission today.
People who make few or no long-distance calls could see their bills drop by as
much as 50 percent. The commission cut by $3.2 billion the ''access fees'' that
local phone companies charge long-distance carriers to connect calls -- costs
that are typically assessed to consumers. Long-distance companies have pledged
to pass on the savings, meaning their customers should see lower rates.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Witnesses Offered Against Microsoft Breakup
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft, filing a last brief before the federal judge
weighing its antitrust penalty, offered top executives from Compaq, DreamWorks
and other companies today as potential witnesses against breaking up the
software giant. In an additional ''offer of proof,'' Microsoft's lawyers said
Jeffrey Katzenberg of DreamWorks and Michael Kapellas of Compaq, among others,
would testify to the negative effects that a government-backed Microsoft breakup
would have on their companies and industries.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 5; Nasdaq Drops 59
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as investors doubted whether
the Federal Reserve is ready to end its interest-rate hikes. The Dow Jones
industrial average slipped 4.80 to 10,522.33. On the NYSE, gainers led losers
1,725-1,265. The Nasdaq fell 58.57 to 3,400.91.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ewing Returns for Knicks
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Patrick Ewing returned to the New York Knicks' starting
lineup tonight after missing the last two playoff games with tendinitis in his
right foot. The Knicks faced the Indiana Pacers in Game 5 of the Eastern
Conference finals with the best-of-seven series tied 2-2. Larry Johnson also
started for the Knicks despite a case of plantar fasciitis in his right foot.
</P>
