<DOCNO> APW20000531.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dodgers' Hundley Placed on DL  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Catcher Todd Hundley was placed on the 15-day
disabled list Wednesday by the Los Angeles Dodgers because of a
strained rib cage muscle.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, batting .290 with 13 homers and 33 RBIs, strained the
abdominal oblique muscle in his right rib cage Tuesday night while
running the bases in a 10-5 loss to the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel like I have a knife stuck in me right now,'' Hundley
said before the finale of the three-game series. ''On the average,
injuries like this take three to six weeks till you feel 100
percent, but there's no guarantees.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only good thing about it is that it's not the cartilage
between the ribs. That could be six months because the rib cage is
very delicate. But we have it centered, and we know exactly where
it's at.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11-year veteran, who broke Roy Campanella's major league
record for catchers with 41 home runs in 1996 with the Mets, was
finally feeling 100 percent healthy for the first time since
undergoing elbow surgery in September 1997 before this latest
mishap.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just a little bump in the road,'' Hundley said. ''Now
I've got to work twice as hard to get back from this, once the
doctors clear me and say it's safe to go back to lifting weights
and working out again. It'll be real delicate the next two weeks.
The trick is not to aggravate it and start all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The incident occurred in the sixth inning, following Hundley's
leadoff double. He took off on a broken-bat single to center by
Dave Hansen, and was about five steps from third base when he
turned to his right to see if center fielder Melvin Mora would have
a chance to make at play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, Hundley felt a burning sensation and eased up. A few
minutes later, he staggered off the field and into the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole muscle went,'' said Hundley, who was examined
Wednesday morning by doctors Frank Jobe and Ralph Gambardella.
''The way it was explained to me, the muscle completely expanded
and then completely contracted -- all in one shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley, who turned 31 last Saturday, is going on the DL for the
fourth time in his career. Backup catcher Chad Kreuter, whose
eight-game suspension stemming from an altercation in the stands
with a fan at Wrigley Field is under appeal, started Wednesday
night's game for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Infielder Alex Cora was recalled from Triple-A Albuquerque to
fill Hundley's roster spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 2203 </TRAILER>
