<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philly School Takeover Averted  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Mayor John F. Street announced a plan
Wednesday to bail out the Philadelphia schools, averting a state
takeover of the financially strapped school district -- at least
through next year.
</P>
<P>
   The state will put up nearly $70 million through deferred taxes
and the city will add $20 million under the plan, though Street
said it was unclear how the city would come up with its share of
the money. The school board approved also about $30 million in cuts
Wednesday, primarily in administrative offices, teacher training
programs and staffing in a comprehensive day-care program.
</P>
<P>
   The state agreed it will not take over the schools under that
deal, Street and Gov. Tom Ridge said.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 law allows the governor to take over the city's schools
if the school board does not produce a valid budget or state
officials determine that it is not educating pupils well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a good agreement for the city, and a good agreement
for the state,'' Ridge said. ''It gives Philadelphia parents the
certainty they deserve that their schools will be open next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Street said the deal was good for Philadelphia's children.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think there can't be a world-class city if we have a
second-class education system,'' Street said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the temporary solution, the school district's budget
crisis is not over, the mayor said. The city and state still must
work out a long-term solution to the school district's perpetual
budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   After Street's announcement, the Philadelphia School Board
approved about $30 million in cuts to help reduce the budget
shortfall. The 2001 budget still has an $80 million lump-sum
deficit, board member Rhonda Chatzkel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 2211 </TRAILER>
