<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressJohn Coolidge:
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) -- John Coolidge, the oldest living
offspring of an American president, died Wednesday of respiratory
problems. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Coolidge was the son of President Calvin Coolidge who became
president in 1923 upon the death of Warren Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Coolidge won election in his own right in 1924 but
decided against re-election in 1928.
</P>
<P>
   John Coolidge spent most of his adult life in Connecticut where
he was a railroad executive and operated a business in Hartford. He
also worked to preserve the buildings that make up the President
Calvin Coolidge State Historic Site.
John Sunshine Darley:
</P>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- John Sunshine Darley, a pilot who taught such
celebrities as singer John Denver and actor Cliff Robertson to fly,
died Sunday. He was 81.
</P>
<P>
   Darley, who left his native Philippines for the United States in
1941, was the first private citizen to be appointed as a Federal
Aviation Administration examiner. He was inducted into the Colorado
Aviation Hall of Fame in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife started Aero Training of the Rockies in 1970.
His students included Denver and Robertson.
Donald W. Davies:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Donald W. Davies, whose pioneering work on data
transmission contributed to the development of the Internet, died
Sunday. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   Working at the National Physical Laboratory, Davies is credited
with coining the term ''packet switching'' in 1966 for data
transmission that is fundamental to the workings of the Internet.
He also led a team that built one of the first functioning networks
using packet data.
</P>
<P>
   Davies' team presented its paper at a 1967 conference in
Tennessee where Lawrence Roberts of the Advanced Research Projects
Agency of the U.S. Department of Defense presented a design for
creating a computer network. In the United States, this led to the
development of ARPANET, the prototype for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   His books included ''Communication Networks for Computers'' in
1973, ''Computer Networks and their Protocols'' in 1979, and
''Security for Computer Networks'' in 1984.
Robert Fryer:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Robert Fryer, a producer of some of
Broadway's best-known musicals, including ''Wonderful Town,''
''Sweet Charity,'' ''Mame'' and ''Chicago,'' died Sunday of
complications from Parkinson's disease. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Fryer usually produced with such partners as George Abbott,
Lawrence Carr, Mary Lea Johnson and James Nederlander.
</P>
<P>
   In 1951, he produced ''A Tree Grows in Brooklyn,'' a musical
version of the best-selling Betty Smith novel.
</P>
<P>
   He had his first big success in 1953 with ''Wonderful Town,'' a
musical adaptation of ''My Sister Eileen,'' featuring a score by
Leonard Bernstein, Betty Comden and Adolph Green. The musical won
five Tony Awards, including one for its star, Rosalind Russell.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later was ''Auntie Mame,'' another hit. He also
produced the musical version of the comedy, retitled ''Mame,''
which starred Angela Lansbury. Opening in 1966, the show ran 1,508
performances, the longest of any of Fryer's Broadway productions.
</P>
<P>
   That same year, he had another hit musical, ''Sweet Charity,''
starring Gwen Verdon.
</P>
<P>
   In 1975, Fryer brought to Broadway the original production of
''Chicago.''
</P>
<P>
   He also made several films that received Oscar nominations. His
movies include ''The Prime of Miss Jane Brodie,'' ''Travels With My
Aunt,'' ''The Boys From Brazil'' and ''The Shining.''
David Levinson:
</P>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- David Levinson, former managing editor
of the Long Beach Press-Telegram, died Tuesday of cancer. He was
70.
</P>
<P>
   He was hired as an editorial writer for the Press-Telegram in
1970. Levinson also worked as a features copy editor and music
critic, covering the Long Beach Symphony. He soon rose to the rank
of managing editor, a post he held until retiring in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Levinson had a lifelong fascination with used and rare books,
and turned his hobby into an at-home Internet business called Book
Brothers.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife and two sons.
Petter Lindstrom:
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Dr. Petter Lindstrom, a neurosurgeon who was
abandoned by wife Ingrid Bergman in a high-profile affair a
half-century ago, died May 24. He was 93.
</P>
<P>
   Lindstrom was married to Bergman for 10 years, moving with her
from Sweden to the United States when her acting career took off
here in the late '30s and early '40s.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman began an affair with Italian director Roberto Rossellini
in 1948, leaving her husband and their daughter, Pia, to live with
Rossellini in Italy. She bore him a son, Roberto.
</P>
<P>
   The love triangle and out-of-wedlock birth shocked Bergman fans
who were used to seeing the screen idol playing nuns and martyrs.
The U.S. Senate even denounced the affair from the floor.
</P>
<P>
   She divorced Lindstrom in 1950 to marry Rossellini, and their
eight-year marriage produced two more children, Ingrid and
Isabella. Isabella Rossellini became a noted actress in her own
right. Bergman died in 1982.
Lord MacLehose:
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Former Hong Kong Gov. Lord MacLehose, the first
official to discuss the delicate issue of handing over the British
colony with Beijing, died Saturday. He was 82.
</P>
<P>
   As the British governor of Hong Kong from 1971 to 1982,
MacLehose oversaw the colony's development from a small trading
post into one of the most important industrial and commercial
centers in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   He also took a pragmatic approach to relations with China,
particularly as Britain's 99-year lease on the colony was quickly
approaching its end. In July 1997, Hong Kong -- a British colony for
156 years -- was formally handed back to China.
</P>
<P>
   It became a Special Administrative Region in China, with
guaranteed autonomy under a so-called ''one country, two systems''
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure, MacLehose tried to improve relations with
Beijing. He was the first governor to celebrate China Day and he
made a successful visit to the Chinese capital in 1979. When
MacLehose returned from the meetings, he reportedly assured Hong
Kong business leaders that they could ''put their hearts at ease.''
Joe Massimino:
</P>
<P>
   TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) -- Joe Massimino, longtime band leader for
''The Mike Douglas Show,'' died May 24 of complications from
stomach cancer. He was 64.
</P>
<P>
   Massimino won an Emmy during his 15 years leading the band for
talk show host Douglas.
</P>
<P>
   At 17, he was hired to play in Tommy Dorsey's band after an
audition where he impressed the big band leader by ripping through
Dorsey's ''T.D. Boogie,'' a tune he had committed to memory.
</P>
<P>
   He toured with Dorsey for three years, and went on to musical
associations with ''Tonight Show'' bandleader Doc Severinsen,
singer Joe Williams and the big bands of Buddy Rich and Louis
Bellson.
</P>
<P>
   Massimino was known as a be-bop-based improviser who usually
worked at an acoustic piano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
