<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 22:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Miss. Jumper Beats World Leader  </HEADLINE>
By BERT ROSENTHAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURHAM, N.C. (AP) -- Superman reigned supreme.
</P>
<P>
   Mississippi's Savante Stringfellow, who has Superman tattoos on
his biceps and calf and wears a Superman T-shirt during warmups,
won the men's long jump at the NCAA Track and Field Championships
on Wednesday night, beating world leader Melvin Lister of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Stringfellow, last year's national champion but the runner-up to
Lister at this season's Southeastern Conference Championships,
soared 26 feet, 9} inches, and had four of the five best jumps in
the competition in beating his rival for the third time in five
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   His other big jumps were 26-8\ and two at 26-5 before fouling on
his final two attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ''I tried to come out and set the tone,'' said Stringfellow,
ranked fourth in the world this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I knew so much was riding on this. This was Melvin's last
collegiate long jump and I didn't want to make it a happy
celebration for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister, the defending champion and with a best of 27-10\ at the
SEC Championships, appeared listless, finishing fourth at 26-0.
</P>
<P>
   ''He looked lackadaisical out there,'' Arkansas jumps coach Dick
Booth said after watching Lister's first three attempts. ''He's not
running fast. He's got to hit it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister never hit it, going 25-1}, 25-4}, 25-11 and fouling twice
before reaching his best on his final attempt.
</P>
<P>
   ''That was the worst Melvin Lister you'll ever see,'' the
Razorbacks' star said. ''You'll never see that Melvin Lister again.
I wasn't into it. I had a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   Lister had swept the long jump and triple jump at the NCAA
Indoor Championships in March, when Stringfellow failed to qualify
for the long jump final, and was favored to repeat at the outdoor
championships. He'll get a shot to redeem himself in the triple
jump final Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Auburn discus thrower Gabor Mate, who continually
watches films of 1976 Olympic champion Mac Wilkins, won a gold
medal for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   To cap his performance, the sophomore from Hungary smashed
Wilkins' 18-year-old stadium record with a toss of 215-8 on his
final throw. Wilkins had set the mark of 212-6 in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm proud I broke the Olympic champion stadium's record,'' the
fun-loving Mate said. ''He was an awesome thrower.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's one of my idols because of his consistency in meets. His
distances were impressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Mate opened with a big throw and was so elated that he kissed
the ground. After his final throw, he kissed his left footprint
where he started in the back of the discus circle.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before the first throw, I felt a lot of pressure to perform
well and pull out a good throw,'' Mate said. ''Afterward, I felt
relief.
</P>
<P>
   ''After the last throw, I had a special feeling for the meet. I
like to do something special, something unique, something
original.''
</P>
<P>
   Mate did something unusual earlier in the season. He and
roommate Reedus Thurmond, who finished third at 203-7, decided that
whoever surpassed 215 feet would have to dye his hair. Mate did it
March 26, setting the collegiate record of 219-6. So his
brownish-black hair now has a lot of blonde flowing through it.
</P>
<P>
   That won't last long. After winning the national title again,
Mate said he would dye his hair orange and blue -- Auburn's colors.
</P>
<P>
   Before this season, Mate had set a modest goal of making the
Hungarian Olympic team. Now, his aim is much loftier.
</P>
<P>
   ''As my performances grew, I got greedier,'' he said. ''I think
the Olympic final will be my goal now.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, SMU's Florence Ezeh won her second consecutive
women's hammer throw title with a meet-record 211-10, breaking the
previous mark of 209-4 by South Carolina's Lisa Misipeka set in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ezeh, who is unbeaten this year, also won the 20-pound weight
throw title indoors. The indoor victory came on her final attempt.
The outdoor championship was less dramatic, her best throw coming
on her fourth of six attempts.
</P>
<P>
   It took a while for Ezeh, a native of France, to get going
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ''On my first throw I was so tense I couldn't throw,'' she said.
''On my second, I tried to improve but I couldn't really. The third
didn't work out.
</P>
<P>
   ''Between flights (the third and fourth rounds), since nothing
was working out, I prayed and it happened.''
</P>
<P>
   In the other final, Tara Rohatinsky led a 1-2 BYU finish in the
women's 10,000 meters with a time of 33 minutes, 49.24 seconds.
Marty Hernandez was runner-up in 33:50.45.
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas, favored to win its record-tying ninth consecutive
men's title, saw Sam Glover post the fastest time in the heats of
the 400 hurdles, 49.58, and James Karanu win his 800 heat in
1:47.91, but teammate D'Marcus Brown didn't qualify for Saturday's
hurdles final, Danny Lincoln failed to advance through the heats of
the 3,000 steeplechase and the Razorbacks' 400 relay team placed
last in its qualifying heat.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA, the women's NCAA indoor champion and among the favorites
for the outdoor title, also lost its 400 relay team for Saturday's
final as the Bruins finished last in their heat.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 2233 </TRAILER>
