<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Devil Rays 4, Orioles 3  </HEADLINE>
By FRED GOODALL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Devil Rays finished
off the Baltimore Orioles not once, but twice Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   B.J. Surhoff's grounder off reliever Roberto Hernandez's glove
went to shortstop Felix Martinez, who threw the ball to first for
the final out in Tampa Bay's 4-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After first-base umpire Brian Runge called Surhoff out, the
Devil Rays came on the field to shake hands in celebration of the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Surhoff, Orioles manager Mike Hargrove and first-base
coach Eddie Murray argued the call. That's when third-base ump John
Shulock overruled Runge, saying Fred McGriff's foot came off first
base.
</P>
<P>
   So after a nine-minute delay, which included Tampa Bay manager
Larry Rothschild saying he would play in protest, the game resumed.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Johnson singled before Hernandez struck out Brady
Anderson to end it with the tying run on third.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff's 399th career homer, a two-run shot off Buddy Groom
with one out in the eighth inning, led Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff had gone 36 at-bats since May 17 without a homer when he
pulled a 1-2 pitch into the right-field stands as Baltimore's
bullpen squandered another late-inning lead, this time denying Mike
Mussina a victory.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Mecir (4-1) pitched two-thirds of an inning, while Hernandez
got his fifth save in nine opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina allowed two runs, four hits and struck out five in seven
innings. Groom (3-3) replaced him at the start the eighth and gave
up a leadoff walk to Jose Guillen, who took second on Randy Winn's
sacrifice bunt.
</P>
<P>
   McGriff was stuck in a 7-for-40 slump when he delivered his
game-winning homer, the only extra-base hit by either team.
</P>
<P>
   Will Clark and Cal Ripken Jr. hit RBI singles off Cory Lidle in
the fourth, and Lidle hit Ripken with the bases loaded to force in
a run for a 3-1 lead in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Vinny Castilla had RBI singles in the first and sixth off
Mussina, but the rest of the Devil Rays hitters were 0-for-5 with
runners in scoring position against the Baltimore starter.
</P>
<P>
   Mussina is off to the worst start of his career, primarily
because of poor run support this season. He ended a four-game
losing streak when he beat Seattle last week and was tough on the
Devil Rays after a hit batter, a walk and Castilla's RBI single
gave Tampa Bay a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander retired 12 in a row before Martinez singled
with two outs in the fifth and stole second.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays lost the first two games of the series while
going 3-for-26 with runners in scoring position, and missed out on
another opportunity when Gerald Williams popped out to second base
to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lidle shut down the Orioles for three innings, allowing only two
baserunners before Mike Bordick singled to open the fourth. Clark
went to second when Guillen misplayed his RBI single for an error,
and Ripken followed with his run-scoring single for a 2-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Tampa Bay starter ran into more trouble in the sixth when he
gave up one-out singles to Delino DeShields and Albert Belle and
walked Clark to load the bases. Lidle left after hitting Ripken in
the back to drive in DeShields to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays escaped further damage when reliever Mark Guthrie
struck out Harold Baines and Surhoff flied to deep right.
</P>
<P>
   Castilla's second RBI single trimmed Baltimore's lead to 3-2.
But Mussina got Bubba Trammell to fly out, then struck out Mike
DeFelice with runners at second and third to get out of the jam.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Lidle became the 10th Devil Rays pitcher to start this
season. Anaheim has also used 10, the only other AL team to start
as many. Tampa Bay used 12 different starters in 1998 and 13 last
year ... Baltimore has gotten six or more innings from starting
pitchers in eight consecutive games ... Mussina didn't allow a
homer for the second straight game, and third time overall. He
began the night tied for the league lead with 15 homers allowed. He
yielded 16 all of last season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
