<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Castaway Leaves 'Survivor'  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- And then there were 15 survivors.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the willing castaways of CBS' ''Survivor'' sent one
of their party packing at the end of the reality series' premiere
Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Kindly Sonja -- a 60-ish musician who had proven not as spry as
the others -- became history in the first lap of this endurance
contest staged on a primitive island near Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   By the 13th weekly installment, just one survivor will remain
from the original 16 -- and be $1 million richer.
</P>
<P>
   But even by the end of the first hour, Sonja had stolen viewers'
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ''Go get 'em, you guys,'' she said, gracious even in exile.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the audience need not fret. Next week (which will
cover another three days in the 39-day stay taped earlier this
year), viewers will find the other characters marooned right where
they left them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the carefully selected ''tribesmen,'' truck driver Susan
will likely still be squabbling with Richard, a corporate trainer.
And Rudy, a retired Navy SEAL, will probably be bossing everyone.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they listened to me,'' he told the camera on the first
show, ''they'd all have haircuts. We'd be in formation in the
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, once again, someone will be voted out at the tribal
council meeting. And then there will be 14.
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of buildup, ''Survivor'' may have surprised viewers
by resisting the salacious or even sinister tone some observers
were dreading. The show focuses on roughing it in beautiful
surroundings -- and on the stresses and strains the participants go
through.
</P>
<P>
   The diverse characters (who are split into two rival camps) are
quickly identifiable and involving. A few, like biochemist Ramona
and Sean, the doctor with a nipple ring, are also easy on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   One contestant who is more interesting than either he or the
show's producers might have preferred is Richard Hatch, who, now
back home in Rhode Island, faced a charge of second-degree child
abuse. Last month, he pleaded innocent to allegations he abused his
9-year-old son. The boy said he was forced to go running and his
father wrapped his hands around his neck to move him along when he
tired.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm good to go, survival-wise,'' he confidently told
Wednesday's ''Survivor'' audience. ''People-wise, it'll be a little
more challenging. But I've got the million-dollar check written
already.''
</P>
<P>
   The actual winner, whose identity CBS is jealously guarding, is
yet to be uncovered.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
http://entertainment.cbs.com/network/tvshows/mini/survivor/
</P>
</TEXT>
