<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 23:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State uses conflicts in trooper statements, experts to back charges </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- Prosecutors used conflicting statements
from the troopers involved in a shooting on the New Jersey Turnpike
and detailed forensic evidence that repeatedly discounts the
officers' stories to support attempted murder charges against the
pair.
</P>
<P>
   In two lengthy briefs filed Wednesday, the state outlined its
case against State Police troopers John Hogan and James Kenna,
arguing that grand jury members were right to indict them.
</P>
<P>
   The charges came after an April 23, 1998, motor vehicle stop on
the turnpike. Three of four minorities heading to basketball clinic
in Maryland were shot by Hogan and Kenna during the traffic stop.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's lawyer asked a judge last month to dismiss the charges.
He said the driver of a van told a grand jury he may have jumped on
the accelerator. The troopers maintain they fired in self-defense,
believing the van was headed for them.
</P>
<P>
   In response to those claims, the state offered statements and
grand jury testimony from all four people in the van who said Kenna
banged a flashlight on the passenger side window, broke it and then
opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   ''I put my hands straight up. He looked right at me. I thought I
was safe. He saw I had no weapons. He continued to shoot,''
passenger Danny Reyes told the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan told investigators 14 hours after the incident that he was
on the ground and firing as the van rolled back toward him,
according to the court papers.
</P>
<P>
   A state forensics expert also testified that a painstaking
recreation of the shooting using the actual van and patrol car
showed Hogan fired several times at the side of the van, according
to the court papers.
</P>
<P>
   Forensics expert Dr. Henry Lee testified that at some point
during the incident, the van appears to have slipped into reverse,
slowly drifted back and hit the front of the patrol car.
</P>
<P>
   ''This impact was consistent with the van being placed in
reverse and at idle speed,'' Lee is quoted as telling the grand
jury.
</P>
<P>
   Evidence also showed that the van was averaging 7 mph above the
55 mph speed limit and not 19 mph as the troopers, according to the
court papers. Traffic studies performed by investigators indicated
the van could not have been going faster than an average of 62 mph
as it traveled down the turnpike, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee also testified that the van's wheels could not have spun as
rapidly as Kenna and Hogan claimed they did. The forensic tests
showed that the van could not have been traveling any faster than 4
mph as it went back toward the police car, the court papers said.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking to investigators after the shooting, Kenna said he
did not radio in to supervisors about the traffic stop because
Hogan was using the car's public address system, according to
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hogan told State Police officials that he could not use
the system to tell the driver to pull over, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenna told those officials that he saw the driver put the car in
reverse and back up at a high rate of speed. He then heard Hogan
yelling from behind the van.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan denied that he yelled or shouted during the incident,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan's lawyer, Robert Galuntuci, said prosecutors acted
improperly before the grand jury and jurors were tainted by
allegations of racial profiling.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings fueled claims that State Police troopers routinely
targeted minority motorists for traffic stops and drug prosecution
on the turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the move to dismiss the charges is scheduled for
June 27 before a state Superior Court judge in Mercer County.
</P>
<P>
   Special Prosecutor James J. Gerrow declined to comment Wednesday
on any of the details highlighted in the state's response to
Galuntuci's motion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We said everything in the brief,'' Gerrow said.
</P>
<P>
   In the four-point legal argument, prosecutors said they and the
judge took every step necessary to shield jurors from any bias
related to the racial profiling controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were repeatedly questioned about media accounts, the
state said. In one case, a juror was dismissed after admitting that
she did not stop reading media accounts of the shooting and
investigation, according to the state's brief.
</P>
<P>
   Driver Keshon Moore, 24, of New York, and the passengers
admitted that they were moving around in the van after the traffic
stop, as Hogan and Kenna claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan, 29, of Florence, and Kenna, 28, of Hamilton Square, have
pleaded innocent to the charges. They have been suspended without
pay, pending the outcome of the case.
</P>
<P>
   Public outcry after the shooting led to widespread allegations
of racial profiling by state troopers and a severely critical
report by the Attorney General's Office detailing the practice.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-05-31-00 2343 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
