<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-31 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beach Volleyball Stops Beach Access  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- Construction of the controversial
Olympic beach volleyball stadium has forced restrictions on public
access to the popular Bondi beach.
</P>
<P>
   Access to the shoreline between the construction site and water
has been temporarily restricted for safety reasons, Olympic
Coordination Authority spokesman Bob Bowden said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   He said a combination of high tides, strong wind and a big swell
caused waves to lap against the construction fence.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have agreed to monitor the shoreline as a precaution to see
whether temporary restrictions on access are required for public
safety reasons,'' Bowden said.
</P>
<P>
   Construction of the temporary 10,000-seat stadium has been
dogged by protests from residents, who say it will cause
environmental damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''They've wrecked our beach and turned it into an unsafe, no-go
area,'' said Lenny Kovner, a spokesman for the residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''September is the month of the worst king tides of all. There
is every likelihood there will be days lost during the Olympics
when they won't be able to play volleyball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-05-31-00 2354 </TRAILER>
